e=\u2018Banshee\u2019 Renewed for Third Season by Cinemax - Ratings - TVbytheNumbers.Zap2it.com|work=TVbytheNumbers}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Season3StarrInt\">{{cite web|first=Christina |last=Raddish |title=Antony Starr Talks Banshee Season Three, Why It\u2019s the Most Ambitious Season Yet, the Physical Challenges of the Show, and More |url=http://collider.com/banshee-season-three-antony-starr-interview/ |publisher=Collider |date=January 7, 2015 |accessdate=January 11, 2015 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6VVLKktLK?url=http://collider.com/banshee-season-three-antony-starr-interview/ |archivedate=January 11, 2015 |url-status=live |df=mdy }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Soundtrack2014\">{{cite news|first=Philiana |last=Ng | url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/earshot/banshee-official-soundtrack-details-stream-678424 |title=Cinemax's 'Banshee' Official Soundtrack Details Revealed (Exclusive) |publisher=Prometheus Global Media | work=The Hollywood Reporter |date=February 10, 2014|accessdate=March 1, 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140301202245/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/earshot/banshee-official-soundtrack-details-stream-678424 |archivedate=March 1, 2014  |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"StuntsMisc1\">{{cite web|first=Alison |last=Willmore |url=http://www.indiewire.com/article/television/greg-yaitanes-interview-banshee-hbo?page=2#articleHeaderPanel |title=The Boldest Show You Haven't Heard Of (Yet): Showrunner Greg Yaitanes Talks Cinemax's Pulp Saga 'Banshee' |publisher=[[Indiewire]] |date=January 2, 2014 |accessdate=February 1, 2014 |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20140131233222/http%3A%2F%2Farticles.redeyechicago.com%2F2014-01-24%2Fentertainment%2F46573971_1_yaitanes-banshee-antony-starr%2F2 |archivedate=January 31, 2014 |url-status=live |df=mdy }}</ref>\n}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website|http://www.cinemax.com/banshee/}}\n* {{IMDb title|2017109|Banshee}}\n* {{tv.com show|banshee|Banshee}}\n* {{Metacritic television|banshee|Banshee}}\n\n{{Cinemax}}\n\n[[Category:2010s American crime drama television series]]\n[[Category:2013 American television series debuts]]\n[[Category:2016 American television series endings]]\n[[Category:American action television series]]\n[[Category:HBO original programming]]\n[[Category:Incest in television]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:Cinemax original programming]]\n[[Category:Serial drama television series]]\n[[Category:Television shows filmed in North Carolina]]\n[[Category:Television shows set in Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Television shows filmed in Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Television shows filmed in Pittsburgh]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American action drama television series}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2013}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name          = Banshee\n| image              = TV series - Banshee Title Card.jpg\n| caption            = \n| genre              = {{plain list|\n* [[Action film|Action]]\n* [[Drama film|Drama]]\n* [[Thriller (genre)#Sub-genres|Crime thriller]]\n}}\n| creator            = [[Jonathan Tropper]]<br />[[David Schickler]]\n| starring           = {{plain list|\n* [[Antony Starr]]\n* [[Ivana Mili\u010devi\u0107]]\n* [[Ulrich Thomsen]]\n* [[Frankie Faison]]\n* [[Hoon Lee]]\n* Rus Blackwell\n* [[Matt Servitto]]\n* Demetrius Grosse\n* [[Trieste Kelly Dunn]]\n* Ryann Shane\n* Newton Paquissi\n* [[Lili Simmons]]\n* [[Ben Cross]]\n* [[Anthony Ruivivar]]\n* [[Geno Segers]]\n* [[Afton Williamson]]\n* [[Langley Kirkwood]]\n* Matthew Rauch\n* [[Tom Pelphrey]]\n* [[Chris Coy]]\n}}\n| composer           = Methodic Doubt\n| country            = United States\n| language           = English\n| num_seasons        = 4\n| num_episodes       = 38\n| list_episodes      = List of Banshee episodes\n| executive_producer = Jonathan Tropper<br />David Schickler<br />[[Peter Macdissi]]<br />[[Alan Ball (screenwriter)|Alan Ball]]<br />[[Greg Yaitanes]]<br />[[Ole Christian Madsen|O.C. Madsen]]<br />Adam Targum\n| producer            = Chad Feehan<br />Robert F. Phillips\n| editor              = Chris A. Peterson\n| cinematography      = Christopher Faloona\n| location = [[Charlotte, NC]] and [[Mooresville, NC]] (Season 1-3)<br />[[Vandergrift, Pennsylvania]] {{Small|(Season 4)}}\n| runtime            = 43\u201359 minutes\n| company            = Your Face Goes Here Entertainment<br />Tropper Schickler Productions<br />One Olive\n| distributor        = [[HBO]]\n| channel            = [[Cinemax]]\n| picture_format     = [[1080i]] ([[HDTV]])\n| first_aired        = {{Start date|2013|1|11}}\n| last_aired         = {{End date|2016|5|20}}\n| website            = http://www.cinemax.com/banshee/\n}}\n\n'''''Banshee''''' is an American [[Action (fiction)|action]] television series created by [[Jonathan Tropper]] and [[David Schickler]] originally appearing on the [[Cinemax]] network beginning on January 11, 2013. Set in the small town of Banshee in Pennsylvania [[Amish]] country, the series' main character is an enigmatic ex-con ([[Antony Starr]]), who assumes the identity of Lucas Hood, the town's murdered sheriff, to hide from powerful crime lord Rabbit ([[Ben Cross]]). Imposing his own brand of justice, Hood attempts to reconcile with his former lover, Rabbit's daughter, Anastasia ([[Ivana Mili\u010devi\u0107]]), who has herself adopted an assumed identity, married, and raised a family during Hood's incarceration. Hood struggles to maintain his new identity while still embracing crime alongside his partners Job ([[Hoon Lee]]) and Sugar ([[Frankie Faison]]), and coming into conflict with local kingpin Kai Proctor ([[Ulrich Thomsen]]).\n\nThe series was developed as part of Cinemax's drive to develop original content. A 10-episode second season debuted in January 2014. ''Banshee'' was renewed for a third season that same month, which debuted in January 2015. In February 2015, the series was renewed for an 8-episode fourth and final season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ca.ign.com/articles/2015/02/12/banshee-renewed-for-season-4?abthid=54dcf0e1843c33e828000015|title=Banshee Renewed for Season 4|last=Fowler|first=Matt|work=[[IGN]]|date=February 12, 2015|accessdate=February 12, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/cinemax-cancels-banshee-811754|title=Cinemax Cancels 'Banshee'|last=Goldberg|first=Lesley|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=July 28, 2015|accessdate=July 29, 2015}}</ref> The final episode aired on May 20, 2016.\n\n== Premise ==\nA man is released from prison after serving 15 years for stealing $15 million in diamonds on behalf of his employer, a Ukrainian mob boss named Rabbit. He and his former lover and accomplice, Rabbit's daughter Anastasia (Ana), had already decided to keep the loot for themselves.  Anastasia got away with the diamonds and Rabbit is after the man, thinking he will lead him to his daughter and the diamonds. The man flees to the small fictional Pennsylvanian town of Banshee, where Ana has been living under the alias of Carrie Hopewell, mother of two and wife of the DA. Lucas Hood, the new sheriff, arrives in a bar at the entrance to the town and is immediately killed when he intervenes in a dispute between local criminals and the bar owner. The man takes Hood's identity and has to impersonate the sheriff and deal with ex-Amish crime lord Kai Proctor, sort things out with \"Carrie\" and get his share of the diamonds while evading Rabbit.<ref name=\"Plot1\"/><ref name=\"Plot2\"/>\n\nSeason 1 focuses on Hood's attempts to restore his relationship with Carrie under the looming threat of Rabbit finding them. Hood completely disregards the law while clashing with Proctor and pursuing his often criminal activities, alienating his own deputies. Rabbit eventually tracks him down and Hood surrenders to spare Carrie. Carrie leads some criminal accomplices and the deputies in a raid to free Hood and shoots Rabbit.\n\nSeason 2 deals with tribal chief Alex Longshadow's attempt to build a casino on the reservation which places Sheriff Hood in the middle of a violent struggle between Longshadow and Proctor. Carrie must face up to her past when she is imprisoned for her part in the raid against her father. With Carrie trying to fix her marriage, Hood enters into a relationship with his deputy Siobhan.<ref name=\"Series1General2\"/> He must deal with the real Hood's son when he comes to Banshee looking for his father.<ref name=\"Season2Jason\"/> Hood and Carrie are forced to track down and confront Rabbit and settle things once and for all when they learn he survived being shot.<ref name=\"S2E10Review\"/>\n\n==Episodes==\n{{main|List of Banshee episodes}}\n{{:List of Banshee episodes}}\n\n== Cast ==\n=== Starring ===\n* [[Antony Starr]] as the man known as Lucas Hood: An ex-con and master thief released from prison after 15 years who adopts the identity of the real Lucas Hood, Banshee's incoming sheriff, who dies in the premiere episode.  The character's real name is never revealed.\n* [[Ivana Mili\u010devi\u0107]] as Anastasiya \"Ana\" Rabitova / Carrie Hopewell: Hood's former criminal accomplice and lover. She lives in Banshee under an alias as a real estate agent with her husband Gordon and children Deva and Max, who are unaware of her past. She is also in hiding from \"Mr. Rabbit\", her father. \n* [[Ulrich Thomsen]] as Kai Proctor: A crime kingpin and businessman in Banshee. Proctor was originally a member of Banshee's Amish community, but abandoned the faith for crime.\n* [[Frankie Faison]] as Sugar Bates: A retired former boxer and ex-con, turned bar owner. He befriends Hood and is aware that he is a criminal.\n* [[Hoon Lee]] as Job: A computer hacker and Hood's criminal accomplice. Job is a [[Transvestism|transvestite]].<ref name=\"CastJob10\"/><ref name=\"CashJob11\"/><ref name=\"CastJob12\"/> He is also in hiding from \"Mr. Rabbit\", and is forced to move to Banshee after his identity is uncovered.\n* [[Rus Blackwell]] as Gordon Hopewell: Banshee's district attorney and Carrie's husband. He is a Gulf War hero and retired Marine. (season 1-3)\n* [[Matt Servitto]] as Brock Lotus: A Banshee deputy, and the longest-serving member of the force.<ref name=\"DevelopmentCasting\"/> Brock was intended to become the new Sheriff before the real Hood's appointment and is resentful of being passed over.\n* [[Demetrius Grosse]] as Emmett Yawners: A male Banshee deputy. (main seasons 1\u20132)\n* [[Trieste Kelly Dunn]] as Siobhan Kelly: A female Banshee deputy. (main seasons 1\u20133)\n* Ryann Shane as Deva Hopewell: A rebellious teenager, daughter of Carrie and Hood.\n* Daniel Ross Owens as Daniel \"Dan\" Kendall: Banshee's mayor, an idealist and a young politician opposed to Proctor's criminal activities. (season 1)\n* [[Lili Simmons]] as Rebecca Bowman:  A young ex-Amish girl who lived a devout life with her father Elijah by day, but was a rebellious, sexually adulterous by night until her family discovers her double life and kicks her out. She is Proctor's niece and the only member of the Amish community he has contact with. Her uncle takes her under his wing and starts mentoring her in the life of crime.\n* [[Ben Cross]] as Igor \"Mr. Rabbit\" Rabitov: A ruthless Ukrainian gangster seeking revenge on Hood for stealing from him, and turning his daughter Anastasia against him. (seasons 1\u20132)\n* [[Anthony Ruivivar]] as Alexander \"Alex\" Longshadow: Indian tribal chief and Proctor's rival. (recurring season 1, main season 2, guest season 3)\n* [[Geno Segers]] as Chayton Littlestone: The imposing leader of the local Kinaho tribal gang the Redbones. (main season 3, guest seasons 2 and 4)\n* [[Afton Williamson]] as Alison Medding: Assistant District Attorney Alison Medding. (recurring season 2, main season 3)<ref name=\"tvline.com\">{{cite web|url=http://tvline.com/2014/04/16/banshee-season-3-geno-segers-afton-williamson-series-regulars/|title=\u2018Banshee\u2019 Season 3: Geno Segers, Afton Williamson Made Series Regulars - TVLine|author=Michael Ausiello|work=TVLine}}</ref> \n* [[Langley Kirkwood]] as Colonel Douglas Stowe: A U.S. Marine running an illegal business out of Banshee's Camp Genoa. (season 3)<ref name=\"CastKirkwood\"/> \n* [[Matthew Rauch]] as Clayton \"Clay\" Burton: Proctor's ruthless right-hand man. (recurring seasons 1\u20133, main season 4)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2015/03/matthew-rauch-promoted-regular-banshee-casey-labow-cast-1201394760/|title=Matthew Rauch Upped To Regular On \u2018Banshee'; Casey LaBow Joins Cast|author=Denise Petski|website=Deadline Hollywood}}</ref>\n* [[Tom Pelphrey]] as Kurt Bunker: A former member of the Aryan Brotherhood who becomes a Banshee deputy. (recurring season 3, main season 4)\n* [[Chris Coy]] as Calvin Bunker: The leader of the Aryan Brotherhood in Banshee and the younger brother of Kurt Bunker. (recurring season 3, main season 4)\n\n===Recurring===\n{{div col}}\n* [[Odette Annable]] as Nola Longshadow: Alex's sister. (seasons 1\u20133)\n* [[Christos Vasilopoulos]] as Olek: Right-hand-man to \"Mr. Rabbit\". (seasons 1\u20132)\n* [[Joseph Gatt]] as Albino: A prisoner who served time with Hood. (recurring seasons 1\u20132, guest season 4)\n* [[Derek Cecil]] as Dean Xavier: An FBI agent. (seasons 1\u20132)\n* Gabriel Suttle as Max: Carrie and Gordon's son. (recurring seasons 1\u20132, stand-in season 3)\n* Deja Dee as Alma: Employee at Banshee's Sheriff Department. (seasons 1\u20133)\n* Chelsea Cardwell as Beaty: Deva's best friend. (seasons 1\u20133)\n* Robert Treveiler as Jackson Sperling: Kai Proctor's lawyer. (seasons 1\u20133)\n* Harrison Thomas as Jason Hood: The real Lucas Hood's son. (guest season 1, recurring season 2)\n* [[\u017deljko Ivanek]] as Jim Racine: An FBI agent. (season 2)\n* [[Reg E. Cathey]] as Det. Julius Bonner: An [[New York City Police Department|NYPD]] [[Detective]] who had arrested the protagonist after the diamond robbery. (guest season 2)\n* Maya Gilbert as Juliet: A stripper. (season 2)\n* Eddie Cooper as Fat Au: A New York-based crime lord who is an old friend of Hood, Carrie and Job. (seasons 2\u20134)\n* Jennifer Griffin as Leah Proctor: Kai's mother. (seasons 2\u20133)\n* [[Tyson Sullivan]] as Hondo: Key enforcer for the Aryan Brotherhood in Banshee, who works for Kai. (recurring season 2, guest season 3)\n* [[Julian Sands]] as Yulish Rabitov: \"Mr. Rabbit\"'s brother and a priest. (season 2)\n* [[Chaske Spencer]] as Billy Raven: A former officer of the Kinaho Reservation Police Department before becoming a Banshee deputy, who is now considered an outcast by his own people. (recurring season 3, guest season 4)\n* [[Meaghan Rath]] as Aimee King: The sole honest officer in the corrupt Kinaho Reservation Police Department. (season 3)\n* Tanya Clarke as Emily Lotus: Brock's ex-wife. (season 3)\n* [[Happy Anderson]] as Bones Tuesday: A cajun fight club owner whose star fighter is Chayton Littlestone. (season 3)\n* Dennis Flanagan as Leo Fitzpatrick: A computer hacker. (seasons 3\u20134)\n* [[David Harbour]] as Robert Dalton: A black ops agent. (guest seasons 3\u20134)\n* [[Casey LaBow]] as Maggie Bunker: The wife of Calvin Bunker, who wants a better life for her and her son. (season 4)\n* [[Eliza Dushku]] as Special Agent Veronica Dawson: An FBI agent who is incredibly reckless and also has personal demons of her own. She is hunting down a serial killer who has just arrived in Banshee. (season 4)\n* [[Chance Kelly]] as Randall Watts: Maggie's father. (season 4)\n* [[Frederick Weller]] as Declan Bode: A satanist and a serial killer. (season 4)\n* [[Nestor Serrano]] as Emilio Loera: A powerful member of the cartel. (season 4)\n* [[Ana Ayora]] as Nina Cruz: A smart, tough and streetwise Banshee deputy who is also working as a mole for Proctor. (season 4)\n{{div col end}}\n\n== Production ==\n[[File:Banshee promotional poster.jpg|thumb|right|upright|Promotional poster for ''Banshee'']]\n''Banshee'' is part of [[Cinemax|Cinemax's]] attempt to expand its original programming content, and it joins ''[[Strike Back: Project Dawn|Strike Back]]'' (co-produced with [[BSkyB]]) and Steve Kronish's ''[[Sandbox (TV series)|Sandbox]]''. ''Banshee'' premiered on January 11, 2013.<ref name=\"futon\"/> The show was first revealed in August 2011, when it was announced that [[Alan Ball (screenwriter)|Alan Ball]] would produce the crime drama. Ball helped develop the project alongside creators [[Jonathan Tropper]] and [[David Schickler]]. ''Banshee'' was originally set up at Cinemax owner [[HBO]], but moved to Cinemax when it was decided to increase original programming on that network. By August, Cinemax was finalizing casting and financial details with the intention of filming in Spring 2012 in [[North Carolina]].<ref name=\"DevelopmentOrigin\"/><ref name=\"DevelopmentOrigin2\"/> In January 2012, Cinemax ordered ten episodes for the show's first season, with the first episode being directed by [[Greg Yaitanes]].<ref name=\"DevelopmentOrigin2\"/> In March 2012, Servitto, Dunn and Owens were cast as, respectively, Brock Lotus, Siobhan Kelly, and Mayor Dan Kendall.<ref name=\"DevelopmentCasting\"/> Later that month, Starr was cast as lead character Lucas Hood, alongside Grosse as deputy Emmett Yawners, Thomsen as Kai Proctor, Lee as Job, and Milicevic as Carrie Hopewell.<ref name=\"DevelopmentCasting3\"/><ref name=\"DevelopmentCasting4\"/><ref name=\"DevelopmentCasting7\"/> Simmons was cast in April as Proctor's niece, Rebecca Bowman, an Amish girl who lives a rebellious double life,<ref name=\"DevelopmentCasting5\"/> and in August 2012, Odette Annable was cast in the recurring role of Nola Longshadow, a Native American assassin.<ref name=\"DevelopmentCasting6\"/> Tropper, Schickler, Ball, Yaitanes and [[Peter Macdissi]] serve as executive producers.<ref name=\"SeasonOneProducers\"/>\n\nDuring the first day of shooting on the series, Starr suffered a facial injury when stunt fight choreography went wrong, splitting his lip open. He continued to film for six hours to complete the scene before going to the hospital to receive six stitches. The injury required digital removal for all scenes set before the fight but filmed after the stunt, resulting in lengthy post-production on the first episode. Some of the many fight scenes on the show can take up to 25 hours to film.<ref name=\"Series1General\"/> Yaitanes cited [[Jason Statham]]-starring action films, and [[John Carpenter]] films ''[[Big Trouble in Little China]]'' (1986) and ''[[They Live]]'' (1988) as inspiration for the fights and violence in ''Banshee''. Marcus Young serves as the series' fight choreographer.<ref name=\"StuntsMisc1\"/>\n\nOn January 29, 2013 Cinemax renewed ''Banshee'' for a 10-episode second season which premiered on January 10, 2014.<ref name=\"Season2B\"/><ref name=\"season2\"/> The season's opening action set piece featuring Milicevic, Starr, and Lee, performing a high-speed heist, was filmed across five miles of closed highway. Tropper originally wrote the scene for the show's accompanying graphic novel, ''Banshee Origins'' which follows the trio sixteen years earlier, but he decided that it would be an interesting live action stunt.<ref name=\"Season2Ep1Stunt\"/> The season finale's shoot out was filmed inside a church in Harlem, New York. The scene was shot over three days.<ref name=\"Season3StarrInt\"/>\n\nAfter three episodes of the second season had aired, ''Banshee'' was renewed for third season,<ref name=\"Season3Renew\"/> which premiered on January 9, 2015.<ref name=\"Season3Premiere\"/>\n\nFor the first three seasons, filming took place mainly in the [[Mooresville, North Carolina]] area. In addition to Mooresville, other area locations were used including Huntersville, Mount Ulla, Lincolnton, Salisbury, Charlotte, Monroe, Gastonia and Waxhaw. Because [[North Carolina General Assembly|North Carolina's legislature]] chose not to continue tax credits for filming movies and TV series, the show moved to the [[Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania]] area, centering in the suburb of [[Vandergrift, Pennsylvania]]. Pennsylvania has continued to offer tax incentives.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://triblive.com/neighborhoods/yourallekiskivalley/yourallekiskivalleymore/8301549-74/street-vandergrift-banshee#axzz3ZmTtYSea |title='Banshee' to begin filming in Vandergrift}}</ref>\n\n== Reception ==\nThe first season of ''Banshee'' received a 64% score on [[Rotten Tomatoes]], an average rating of 6.05/10, sampled from 33 reviews.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/banshee/s01/ |title=Banshee: Season 1 (2013) |work=Rotten Tomatoes |accessdate=August 25, 2015}}</ref> Seasons 2, 3, and 4 received scores of 93%, 100%, and 100% respectively.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/banshee/|title=Banshee|website= [[Rotten Tomatoes]] }}</ref> On [[Metacritic]] it has a weighted average score of 61/100 based on reviews from 29 critics, indicating \"generally favorable reviews.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Banshee |url= http://www.metacritic.com/tv/banshee/ |website= [[Metacritic]] |publisher=CBS Interactive}}</ref>\n\n''[[Wall Street Journal]]'' critic Dorothy Rabinowitz wrote, \"Its smartness comes shining through despite the claptrap (none worse than the parade of sex scenes, soft-porn variety, whose noisiness is exceeded only by their unconvincingness); its story, littered with intriguingly repellent characters, like Kai Proctor (Ulrich Thomsen), local evil tycoon, grows ever more enticing\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Wall street Journal Review|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424127887324081704578233710443186102|newspaper=Wall street journal}}</ref> The ''[[San Francisco Chronicle]]'' said about Banshee, \"It has a solid pedigree. It's also part of Cinemax's effort to expand its original programming. That effort pays off with Banshee\".<ref name=\"San Francisco Chronicle\">{{cite news|title=San Francisco Chronicle review|url=http://www.post-gazette.com/stories/ae/tv-radio/tuned-in-from-hollywood-banshee-an-engrossing-crime-drama-justified-starts-strong-669769/|newspaper=San Francisco Chronicle | first=Rob|last=Owen|date=January 10, 2013}}</ref> ''[[The A.V. Club]]'' included season 3 on its list of the best TV of 2015, describing it as \"upping the emotional stakes to almost unbearable levels.\"<ref>{{cite web |date= 2015-12-15 |last1= Kulzick |first1= Kate |title= The best TV of 2015, part 1 |url= https://tv.avclub.com/the-best-tv-of-2015-part-1-1798287313 |website= [[The A.V. Club]] |publisher= [[The Onion]] }}</ref>\n\n''Banshee'' has also had less favorable reviews. A ''[[Boston Herald]]'' critic described the series as: \"A slow-pokey drama punctuated by shocking violence and sex\".<ref name=\"Boston Herald\">{{cite news|title=Boston herald Review|url=http://bostonherald.com/entertainment/television/television_reviews/2013/01/amish_meet_violence_sex_%E2%80%98banshee%E2%80%99|newspaper=Boston Herald}}</ref>\n\n=== Ratings ===\nSeason one of ''Banshee'' drew Cinemax's then-highest ratings for an original series, averaging 433,000 viewers per episode and 727,000 in the 7 days after each episode was released. The season finale drew 455,000 viewers during its initial screening and 655,000 during its repeat, the largest audience ever, at the time, for a Cinemax original series, and the third-highest ratings achieved by ''Banshee'' at that point.<ref name=\"RatingsSeason1\"/>\n\nThe second season exceeded the first's successes. The season's fifth episode, \"The Truth about Unicorns\", set a series record with 591,000 viewers during its original airing. The season finale also set a new record, with 733,000 viewers, and a total of 968,000 for the evening including repeat showings.<ref name=\"RatingsSeason2\"/>\n\n=== Accolades ===\n[[Armen V. Kevorkian]] won the award for [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Special Visual Effects|Outstanding Special Visual Effects]] at the [[65th Primetime Creative Arts Emmy Awards]].<ref name=\"2012Emmy\"/>\n\n== Other media ==\nA soundtrack album, ''Banshee \u2013 Music from the Cinemax Original Series'', was released as digital download on February 11, 2014. The album features 17 songs from the show's first two seasons, including the main theme by Methodic Doubt, and tracks by artists including [[Nico Vega]], [[Ivy Levan]], [[The Growl]], [[Anders Osborne]], [[Fred Eaglesmith]], and [[Martin Harley (musician)|Martin Harley]].<ref name=\"Soundtrack2014\"/>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|refs=\n\n<ref name=\"2012Emmy\">{{cite web|title=2013 Creative Arts Emmys Winners |url=http://www.emmys.com/sites/default/files/2013CreativeArtsEmmysWinners.pdf |work=[[Academy of Television Arts & Sciences]] |date=September 15, 2013 |accessdate=February 1, 2014 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6N4Bh1o8K?url=http://www.emmys.com/sites/default/files/2013CreativeArtsEmmysWinners.pdf |archivedate=February 1, 2014 |url-status=live |df=mdy }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"CastJob10\">{{cite web|url=http://audreymagazine.com/hoon-lee-how-to-play-a-foul-mouthed-transvestite-hacking-genius-with-aplomb/|title=HOON LEE: How To Play A Foul-Mouthed, Transvestite Hacking Genius With Aplomb|date=January 14, 2014|accessdate=April 26, 2014}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"CashJob11\">{{cite web|url=http://collider.com/hoon-leet-banshee-interview/|title=Hoon Lee Talks Banshee, Action Scenes in Heels, and Voicing Splinter in the Teenage Mutant Ninja Turtles Animated Series|last=Radish|first=Christina|work=Collider.com|accessdate=April 26, 2014}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"CastJob12\">{{cite web|url=http://www.sfgate.com/tv/article/Banshee-review-Sheriff-steals-the-show-4184529.php|title='Banshee' review: Sheriff steals the show|last=Wiegand|first=David|work=sfgate.com|date=January 10, 2013|accessdate=April 26, 2014}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"CastKirkwood\">{{cite web|url=http://www.spoilertv.com/2014/04/banshee-season-3-langley-kirkwood-joins.html|title=Banshee - Season 3 -  Langley Kirkwood joins as Regular, 3 others get Recurring Roles|work=SpoilerTV}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"DevelopmentCasting\">{{cite web|first=Nellie |last=Andreeva |url=http://www.deadline.com/2012/03/trio-cast-in-cinemax-series-banshee/ |title=Trio Cast In Cinemax Series \u2018Banshee\u2019 |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=March 2, 2012 |accessdate=January 30, 2014 |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20140130232536/http%3A%2F%2Fwww.deadline.com%2F2012%2F03%2Ftrio-cast-in-cinemax-series-banshee%2F |archivedate=January 30, 2014 |url-status=live |df=mdy }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"DevelopmentCasting3\">{{cite web|first=Nellie |last=Andreeva |url=http://www.deadline.com/2012/03/cinemaxs-alan-ball-produced-new-series-banshee-casts-antony-starr-as-its-lead/ |title=Cinemax\u2019s Alan Ball-Produced New Series \u2018Banshee\u2019 Casts Antony Starr As Its Lead |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=March 12, 2012 |accessdate=January 31, 2014 |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20140131230502/http%3A%2F%2Fwww.deadline.com%2F2012%2F03%2Fcinemaxs-alan-ball-produced-new-series-banshee-casts-antony-starr-as-its-lead%2F |archivedate=January 31, 2014 |url-status=live |df=mdy }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"DevelopmentCasting4\">{{cite news|first=Lesley |last=Goldberg |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/ulrich-thomsen-alan-ball-banshee-cinemax-300190 |title='Bond' Henchman to Co-Star in Alan Ball's Cinemax Drama 'Banshee' |publisher=Prometheus Global Media |work=The Hollywood Reporter |date=March 14, 2012 |accessdate=January 31, 2014 |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20140131231003/http%3A%2F%2Fwww.hollywoodreporter.com%2Flive-feed%2Fulrich-thomsen-alan-ball-banshee-cinemax-300190 |archivedate=January 31, 2014 |url-status=live |df=mdy }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"DevelopmentCasting5\">{{cite news|first=Michael |last=Ausiello |url=http://tvline.com/2012/04/10/lili-simmons-banshee-cinemax/ |title=Exclusive: Disney Channel Starlet Takes Racy Turn in Cinemax Drama Series Banshee |publisher=[[TVLine]] |date=April 10, 2012 |accessdate=February 1, 2014 |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20140201150801/http%3A%2F%2Ftvline.com%2F2012%2F04%2F10%2Flili-simmons-banshee-cinemax%2F |archivedate=February 1, 2014 |url-status=live |df=mdy }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"DevelopmentCasting6\">{{cite news|first=Michael |last=Ausiello |url=http://tvline.com/2012/08/06/banshee-odette-annable-cinemax/ |title=Exclusive: House Reunion on Cinemax's Banshee as Odette Annable Reteams With Greg Yaitanes |publisher=[[TVLine]] |date=August 6, 2012 |accessdate=February 1, 2014 |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20140201151001/http%3A%2F%2Ftvline.com%2F2012%2F08%2F06%2Fbanshee-odette-annable-cinemax%2F |archivedate=February 1, 2014 |url-status=live |df=mdy }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"DevelopmentCasting7\">{{cite web|first=Nellie |last=Andreeva |url=http://www.deadline.com/2012/03/ivana-milicevic-to-star-in-banshee-derek-richardson-joins-anger-management/ |title=Ivana Milicevic To Star In \u2018Banshee\u2019, Derek Richardson Joins \u2018Anger Management\u2019 |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=March 14, 2012 |accessdate=February 1, 2014 |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20140201151248/http%3A%2F%2Fwww.deadline.com%2F2012%2F03%2Fivana-milicevic-to-star-in-banshee-derek-richardson-joins-anger-management%2F |archivedate=February 1, 2014 |url-status=live |df=mdy }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"DevelopmentOrigin\">{{cite news|first=Steven |last=Zeitchik |url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/showtracker/2011/08/alan-ball-true-love-sookie-hbo-cinemax-banshee.html |title='True Blood's' Alan Ball will have a new series -- on Cinemax |date=August 10, 2011 |accessdate=January 30, 2014 |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |publisher=[[Tribune Company]] |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20140130230556/http%3A%2F%2Flatimesblogs.latimes.com%2Fshowtracker%2F2011%2F08%2Falan-ball-true-love-sookie-hbo-cinemax-banshee.html |archivedate=January 30, 2014 |url-status=live |df=mdy }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"DevelopmentOrigin2\">{{cite web|first=Nellie |last=Andreeva |url=http://www.deadline.com/2012/01/alan-balls-drama-banshee-gets-series-order-at-cinemax-greg-yaitanes-to-direct/ |title=Alan Ball\u2019s Drama \u2018Banshee\u2019 Gets Series Order At Cinemax, Greg Yaitanes To Direct |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=January 25, 2012 |accessdate=January 30, 2014 |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20140130232035/http%3A%2F%2Fwww.deadline.com%2F2012%2F01%2Falan-balls-drama-banshee-gets-series-order-at-cinemax-greg-yaitanes-to-direct%2F |archivedate=January 30, 2014 |url-status=live |df=mdy }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"futon\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.thefutoncritic.com/showatch/banshee-cinemax/listings/|title=Shows A-Z&nbsp;\u2013 banshee on cinemax|work=The Futon Critic|accessdate=October 19, 2012}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Plot1\">{{cite web|first=Allison |last=Keene |title=Series Preview: Why You Should Give BANSHEE a Shot |url=http://collider.com/banshee-series-premiere-review/ |publisher=Collider |work= |date=January 11, 2013 |accessdate=February 23, 2013 }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Plot2\">{{cite news|first=James |last=Poniewozik |title=TV Tonight: Banshee |url=http://entertainment.time.com/2013/01/11/tv-tonight-banshee/ |publisher=Time |work= |date=January 11, 2013 |accessdate=February 23, 2013 }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"RatingsSeason1\">{{cite web|first=Nellie |last=Andreeva |title=Cinemax\u2019s \u2018Banshee\u2019 Wraps Solid First Season |url=http://www.deadline.com/2013/03/cinemaxs-banshee-wraps-solid-first-season/ |publisher=[[PMC (company)|PMC]] |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date= March 18, 2013 | accessdate=March 18, 2013 | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140309160456/http://www.deadline.com/2013/03/cinemaxs-banshee-wraps-solid-first-season/ |archivedate=March 9, 2014 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"RatingsSeason2\">{{cite web |title=\u2018Banshee\u2019 Screams Past Cinemax Record |url=http://www.deadline.com/2014/03/banshee-season-finale-cinemax-record/ |publisher=[[PMC (company)|PMC]] |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date= March 17, 2014 | accessdate=March 17, 2014  | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140317221522/http://www.deadline.com/2014/03/banshee-season-finale-cinemax-record/ |archivedate=March 17, 2014 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n<!-- <ref name=\"S2E10Grosse\">{{cite web|first=Andrea|last=Reiher |title='Banshee's' Demetrius Grosse discusses the shocking ending to Season 2 |url=http://blog.zap2it.com/frominsidethebox/2014/03/banshees-demetrius-grosse-discusses-the-shocking-ending-to-season-2.html |publisher=[[Zap2it]] |date=March 14, 2014 |accessdate=March 15, 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140315104546/http://blog.zap2it.com/frominsidethebox/2014/03/banshees-demetrius-grosse-discusses-the-shocking-ending-to-season-2.html |archivedate=March 15, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> -->\n\n<ref name=\"S2E10Review\">{{cite web|first=Les |last=Chappell |title=Banshee: \"Bullets And Tears\"|url=http://www.avclub.com/tvclub/banshee-bullets-and-tears-201976 |publisher=The Onion, Inc. |work=[[The A.V. Club]] |date=March 14, 2014 |accessdate=March 15, 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140315104232/http://www.avclub.com/tvclub/banshee-bullets-and-tears-201976 |archivedate=March 15, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"SeasonOneProducers\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.deadline.com/2011/08/cinemax-prepping-amish-country-series-executive-produced-by-alan-ball/|title=Cinemax Prepping Amish Country Series Executive Produced by Alan Ball|website=Deadline Hollywood|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|date=August 11, 2011|accessdate=August 2, 2012}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Series1General\">{{cite web|first=Curt |last=Wagner |url=http://articles.redeyechicago.com/2014-01-24/entertainment/46573971_1_yaitanes-banshee-antony-starr |title=Antony Starr enjoys his 'Banshee' beatdowns |publisher=[[Chicago Tribune]] |work=RedEye |date=January 24, 2012 |accessdate=January 31, 2014 |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20140131233204/http%3A%2F%2Farticles.redeyechicago.com%2F2014-01-24%2Fentertainment%2F4657