 Boldest Show You Haven't Heard Of (Yet): Showrunner Greg Yaitanes Talks Cinemax's Pulp Saga 'Banshee' |publisher=[[Indiewire]] |date=January 2, 2014 |accessdate=February 1, 2014 |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20140131233222/http%3A%2F%2Farticles.redeyechicago.com%2F2014-01-24%2Fentertainment%2F46573971_1_yaitanes-banshee-antony-starr%2F2 |archivedate=January 31, 2014 |url-status=live |df=mdy }}</ref>\n}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website|http://www.cinemax.com/banshee/}}\n* {{IMDb title|2017109|Banshee}}\n* {{tv.com show|banshee|Banshee}}\n* {{Metacritic television|banshee|Banshee}}\n\n{{Cinemax}}\n\n[[Category:2010s American crime drama television series]]\n[[Category:2013 American television series debuts]]\n[[Category:2016 American television series endings]]\n[[Category:American action television series]]\n[[Category:HBO original programming]]\n[[Category:Incest in television]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:Cinemax original programming]]\n[[Category:Serial drama television series]]\n[[Category:Television shows filmed in North Carolina]]\n[[Category:Television shows set in Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Television shows filmed in Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Television shows filmed in Pittsburgh]]\n", "name_user": "Slade", "label": "safe", "comment": "+refimprove", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Banshee_(TV_series)"}
{"title_page": "The Widow of Montiel", "text_new": "{{short description|1979 film}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name     = The Widow of Montiel\n| image    =La viuda de Montiel film poster.jpg\n| caption = film poster\n| director = [[Miguel Litt\u00edn]] \n| writer   = Miguel Litt\u00edn<br>[[Jos\u00e9 Agust\u00edn]]<br>[[Gabriel Garc\u00eda M\u00e1rquez]]\n| producer = [[Hern\u00e1n Littin]]\n| starring = [[Geraldine Chaplin]]\n| cinematography = Patricio Castilla\n| editing    =  Nelson Rodr\u00edguez\n| released   = {{film date|1979|12|1|df=yes}}\n| country  = Mexico<br>Colombia\n| language = Spanish\n| runtime  = 105 minutes\n}}\n\n'''''The Widow of Montiel''''' ({{lang-es|'''La Viuda de Montiel'''}}) is a 1979 Mexican-Colombian [[drama film]] directed by Chilean filmmaker [[Miguel Litt\u00edn]]. It is based on a short story of the same name by [[Gabriel Garc\u00eda Marquez]]. It was entered into the [[30th Berlin International Film Festival]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.filmaffinity.com/en/film941323.html |title=The Widow of Montiel |work=Film Affinity |accessdate=12 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Geraldine Chaplin]] - Adelaida\n* [[Nelson Villagra]] - Chepe Montiel\n* [[Katy Jurado]] - Mam\u00e1 Grande\n* [[Eduardo Gil]]\n* [[Pilar Romero (actress)|Pilar Romero]] - Hilaria\n* [[Ernesto G\u00f3mez Cruz]] - Carmichael\n* [[Reynaldo Miravalles]]\n* [[Alejandro Parodi]] - Alacaide\n* [[Ignacio Retes]]\n* [[Jorge Feg\u00e1n]]\n* [[Emilia Rojas]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{imdb title|id=0080102|title=The Widow of Montiel}}\n\n{{Miguel Litt\u00edn}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Widow of Montiel, The}}\n[[Category:1979 films]]\n[[Category:1970s drama films]]\n[[Category:Colombian films]]\n[[Category:Mexican films]]\n[[Category:Spanish-language films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Miguel Litt\u00edn]]\n[[Category:Colombian drama films]]\n[[Category:Mexican drama films]]\n[[Category:Films based on works by Gabriel Garc\u00eda M\u00e1rquez]]\n{{1970s-Mexico-film-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|1979 film}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name     = The Widow of Montiel\n| image    =La viuda de Montiel film poster.jpg\n| caption = film poster\n| director = [[Miguel Litt\u00edn]] \n| writer   = Miguel Litt\u00edn<br>[[Jos\u00e9 Agust\u00edn]]<br>[[Gabriel Garc\u00eda M\u00e1rquez]]\n| producer = [[Hern\u00e1n Littin]]\n| starring = [[Geraldine Chaplin]]\n| cinematography = Patricio Castilla\n| editing    =  Nelson Rodr\u00edguez\n| released   = {{film date|1979|12|1|df=yes}}\n| country  = Mexico<br>Colombia\n| language = Spanish\n| runtime  = 105 minutes\n}}\n\n'''''The Widow of Montiel''''' ({{lang-es|'''La Viuda de Montiel'''}}) is a 1979 Mexican-Colombian [[drama film]] directed by Chilean filmmaker [[Miguel Litt\u00edn]]. It is based on a short story of the same name by [[Gabriel Garc\u00eda Marquez]]. It was entered into the [[30th Berlin International Film Festival]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.filmaffinity.com/en/film941323.html |title=The Widow of Montiel |work=Film Affinity |accessdate=12 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Geraldine Chaplin]] - Adelaida\n* [[Nelson Villagra]] - Chepe Montiel\n* [[Katy Jurado]] - Mam\u00e1 Grande\n* [[Eduardo Gil]]\n* [[Pilar Romero (actress)|Pilar Romero]] - Hilaria\n* [[Ernesto G\u00f3mez Cruz]] - Carmichael\n* [[Reynaldo Miravalles]]\n* [[Alejandro Parodi]] - Alacaide\n* [[Ignacio Retes]]\n* [[Jorge Feg\u00e1n]]\n* [[Emilia Rojas]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{imdb title|id=0080102|title=The Widow of Montiel}}\n\n{{Miguel Litt\u00edn}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Widow of Montiel, The}}\n[[Category:1979 films]]\n[[Category:1970s drama films]]\n[[Category:Colombian films]]\n[[Category:Mexican films]]\n[[Category:Spanish-language films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Miguel Litt\u00edn]]\n[[Category:Colombian drama films]]\n[[Category:Mexican drama films]]\n[[Category:Films based on works by Gabriel Garc\u00eda M\u00e1rquez]]\n{{1970s-Mexico-film-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Lugnuts", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Widow_of_Montiel"}
{"title_page": "Red-bellied black snake", "text_new": "{{featured article}}\n{{short description|Highly venomous snake native to eastern Australia}}\n{{About|the snake native to Australia|the snake native to North America|Storeria occipitomaculata}}\n{{speciesbox\n| name = Red-bellied black snake\n | status              = LC\n | status_system       =  IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref name=IUCN>{{cite iucn | title = ''Pseudechis porphyriacus'' | volume= 2017 | page = e.T42493274A42493282 | year = 2017 | doi = 10.2305/IUCN.UK.2018-1.RLTS.T42493274A42493282.en }}</ref>\n| image = Pseudechis porphyriacus (35307320466).jpg\n| image_caption = At [[Lamington National Park]], Queensland\n| genus = Pseudechis\n| species = porphyriacus\n| authority = ([[George Shaw|Shaw]], 1794)\n| range_map = Red-Bellied Range.jpg\n| range_map_caption = Range of red-bellied black snake (in red)\n| synonyms_ref= <ref name=\"AFD\">{{cite web|url=https://biodiversity.org.au/afd/taxa/Pseudechis_porphyriacus |title=Species ''Pseudechis porphyriacus'' (Shaw, 1794) |author=Australian Biological Resources Study|date=26 August 2013|work=Australian Faunal Directory|publisher=Department of the Environment, Water, Heritage and the Arts, Australian Government|accessdate=6 December 2018|location=Canberra, Australian Capital Territory}}</ref><ref>{{EMBL species|genus=Pseudechis|species=porphyriacus}}. www.reptile-database.org.</ref>\n|synonyms= *''Coluber porphyriacus'' <br>{{small|Shaw, 1794}}\n* ''Trimeresurus leptocephalus'' <br>{{small|[[Bernard Germain de Lac\u00e9p\u00e8de|Lac\u00e9p\u00e8de]], 1804}}\n* ''Acanthophis tortor'' <br>{{small|[[Ren\u00e9 Lesson|Lesson]], 1830}}\n* ''Naja porphyrica'' <br>{{small|[[Hermann Schlegel|Schlegel]], 1837}}\n* ''Trimeresurus porphyreus'' <br>{{small|[[Andr\u00e9 Marie Constant Dum\u00e9ril|A.M.C. Dum\u00e9ril]] & [[Gabriel Bibron|Bibron]], 1854}}\n* ''Pseudechis porphyraicus'' [sic] <br>{{small|[[Frederick McCoy|F. McCoy]], 1867}}\n* ''Pseudechys'' [sic] ''porphyriacus'' <br>{{small|\u2014 F. McCoy, 1878}}\n* ''Pseudechis porphyriacus'' <br>{{small|\u2014 [[Harold Cogger|Cogger]], 1983}}\n}}\n\nThe '''red-bellied black snake''' (''Pseudechis porphyriacus'') is a [[species]] of [[venomous snake]] in the [[Family (biology)|family]] [[Elapidae]]. The species is [[endemic]] to [[Australia]]. Originally described by [[George Shaw]] in 1794 as a species new to science, it is one of eastern Australia's most commonly encountered snakes. Averaging around {{convert|1.25|m|abbr=on}} in length, it has glossy black upperparts, bright red or orange flanks, and a pink or dull red belly. It is not an aggressive species and generally retreats from encounters with people, but can attack if provoked.  Although its venom is capable of causing significant illness, no deaths have been recorded from its bite, which is less venomous than other Australian elapid snakes. The venom contains [[neurotoxin]]s, [[myotoxin]]s, and [[Coagulation#Procoagulants|coagulants]] and has [[Hemolysis|haemolytic]] properties; victims can also lose their sense of smell.\n\nCommon in woodlands, forests and swamplands, the red-bellied black snake often ventures into nearby urban areas. It forages in bodies of shallow water, commonly with tangles of water plants and logs, where it hunts its main prey item, frogs, as well as fish, reptiles, and small mammals. The snake is considered to be a [[least-concern species]] according to the [[International Union for Conservation of Nature]], but its numbers are thought to be declining due to habitat fragmentation and decline of frog populations.\n\n==Taxonomy==\nThe red-bellied black snake was first described and named by English naturalist [[George Shaw]] in ''Zoology of New Holland'' (1794) as ''Coluber porphyriacus''.<ref name=shaw/>  Incorrectly assuming it was harmless,<ref name=\"williams\"/> he wrote, \"This beautiful snake, which appears to be unprovided with tubular teeth or fangs, and consequently not of a venomous nature, is three, sometimes four, feet in nature.\"<ref name=shaw>{{cite book | last=Shaw | first=George | year=1794 |title=Zoology of New Holland | location= London, United Kingdom | publisher= J. Sowerby | pages=27\u201328|url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/40653632}}</ref> The species name is derived from the [[Ancient Greek]] ''porphyreus'', which can mean \"dark purple\", \"red-purple\" or \"beauteous\".{{sfn|Liddell|Scott|1980|p=579}} It was the first Australian [[Elapidae|elapid]] snake described.<ref name=\"williams\">{{cite journal|last=Williams|first=David|author2=W\u00fcster, Wolfgang |author2-link=Wolfgang W\u00fcster|author3=Fry, Bryan Grieg |year=2006|title= The good, the bad and the ugly: Australian snake taxonomists and a history of the taxonomy of Australia's venomous snakes|journal=Toxicon|volume=48|pages=919\u201330 |url=https://www.academia.edu/1163367|pmid=16999982|doi=10.1016/j.toxicon.2006.07.016|issue=7}}</ref> The [[syntype]] is presumed lost.<ref name=\"AFD\"/> French naturalist [[Bernard Germain de Lac\u00e9p\u00e8de]] described it under the name ''Trimeresurus leptocephalus'' in 1804.<ref>{{cite journal | last= Lac\u00e9p\u00e8de |first= B.G.E. | year= 1804| title= M\u00e9moire sur plusieurs animaux de la Nouvelle-Hollande dont la description n'a pas encore \u00e9t\u00e9 publi\u00e9e | journal= Annales du Mus\u00e9um National d'Histoire Naturelle. Paris | volume=4 |pages= 184\u2013211 [209]; [pl. 56 fig. 1] | url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/29642955}}</ref> His countryman [[Ren\u00e9 Lesson]] described it as ''Acanthophis tortor'' in 1826.<ref>{{cite book | author= Lesson, R.P. | year= 1826 | chapter= Reptiles. |editor= Duperrey, L.I. |title= Voyage Autour du Monde, Ex\u00e9cut\u00e9 par Ordre du Roi, sur la Corvette de sa Majest\u00e9, La Coquille, Pendant les Ann\u00e9es 1822, 1824 et 1825. Zoologie, Atlas |location= Paris |publisher= Arthus Bertrand | chapter-url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/38768324}}</ref> German biologist [[Hermann Schlegel]] felt it was allied with cobras and called it ''Naja porphyrica'' in 1837.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Schlegel |first1=Hermann |title=Essai sur la Physionomie des Serpens. Partie G\u00e9n\u00e9rale et Partie Descriptive |language=French | volume=2 |date=1837 |publisher=La Haye : Kips & Stockum |pages=479\u201380 |url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/3428921}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Pseudechis porphyriacus (Sowerby).jpg|thumb|left|\"''Coluber porphyriacus''\", ''Zoology and botany of New Holland'' (1794),<ref>Tab. X of: ''Zoology and botany of New Holland and the isles adjacent'' / the zoological part by [[George Shaw]], the botanical part by [[James Edward Smith]]; the figures by [[James Sowerby]].</ref><br>illustration from original description]]\nThe genus ''[[Pseudechis]]'' was created for it by German biologist [[Johann Georg Wagler]] in 1830,<ref>{{cite book | last=Wagler |first=Johann Georg | year= 1830 | title= Nat\u00fcrliches System der Amphibien, mit vorangehender Classification der S\u00e4ugethiere und Vogel | language=German| location=  Munich, Germany | publisher= Cotta'schen |page=[https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_YAsAAAAAQAAJ/page/n178 171] | url=https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_YAsAAAAAQAAJ}}</ref> to which several more species have been added subsequently.<ref>{{cite journal | last=Mackay| first= Roy D. | title= A revision of the genus ''Pseudechis'' | journal=  Proceedings of the Royal Zoological Society of New South Wales | volume= 74th | year=1953\u201354 | pages= 15\u201323 | url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/38812147}}</ref> The name is derived from the Ancient Greek words ''pseud\u0113s'' \"false\",{{sfn|Liddell|Scott|1980|p=795}} and ''echis'' \"viper\".{{sfn|Liddell|Scott|1980|p=295}} Snake expert [[Eric Worrell]], in 1961, analysed the skulls of the genus and found that of the red-bellied black snake to be the most divergent.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Worrell |first1=Eric |authorlink1=Eric Worrell |year=1961 |title=Herpetological name changes |journal=West Australian Naturalist |volume=8 |pages=18\u201327 |url=http://www.hotkeepers.com/aho/pdf/menu2/worrell1963.pdf |accessdate=2012-01-17 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120319192814/http://www.hotkeepers.com/aho/pdf/menu2/worrell1963.pdf |archivedate=2012-03-19 }}</ref> Its position as an early offshoot from the rest of the genus has been confirmed genetically in 2017.<ref name=\"Maddock\">{{Cite journal|last=Maddock|first=Simon T.|last2=Childerstone|first2=Aaron|last3=Fry|first3=Bryan Grieg|last4=Williams|first4=David J.|last5=Barlow|first5=Axel|last6=W\u00fcster|first6=Wolfgang|date=2017 |title=Multi-locus phylogeny and species delimitation of Australo-Papuan blacksnakes (''Pseudechis'' Wagler, 1830: Elapidae: Serpentes)|journal=Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution|volume=107|pages=48\u201355|doi=10.1016/j.ympev.2016.09.005|pmid=27637992|hdl=2436/621498|url=http://espace.library.uq.edu.au/view/UQ:412012/UQ412012_OA.pdf}}</ref>\n\nSnake handler [[Raymond Hoser]] described two extra subspecies in 2003: ''P. p. eipperi'' from the [[Atherton Tableland]] and surrounds in north-east Queensland, which he noted was smaller, rarely attaining 2&nbsp;m (7&nbsp;ft) and had a white or pale pink rather than red belly, and ''P. p.  rentoni'' from southeastern South Australia, which has a variably coloured (often orange or even blueish-tinged) belly. He added that both were disjunct from the main red-bellied black snake population, and as the distinguishing traits of ''P. p. rentoni'' were not consistent, then location was the most reliable way of identifying it.<ref name=hoser2003>{{cite journal | last=Hoser |first= Raymond| year= 2003| title= A re-assessment of the taxonomy of the Red-bellied Black Snakes (Genus ''Pseudechis'') with the descriptions of two new subspecies| journal = Boydii \u2013 Journal of the Herpetological Society of Queensland | issue=Autumn (May)|pages= 15\u201318 | url=http://www.smuggled.com/pdf1/PsePor1.pdf}}</ref> These subspecies have not been recognized by other authors,<ref name=\"AFD\"/> and Hoser has been strongly criticized for identifying some taxa on location alone, and omitting, misinterpreting or inventing evidence of distinctness.<ref name=kaiser13>{{cite journal |last=Kaiser | first= Hinrich | first2= Brian I. |last2=Crother | first3=C.M.R. |last3=Kelly | first4=Luca |last4=Luiselli | first5=Mark |last5=O'Shea | first6=Hidetoshi |last6=Ota | first7=Paulo |last7=Passos | first8=Wulf D. |last8=Schleip | first9=Wolfgang |last9=W\u00fcster | title=Best Practices: In the 21st Century, Taxonomic Decisions in Herpetology are Acceptable Only When Supported by a Body of Evidence and Published via Peer-Review | url=https://www.southeastern.edu/acad_research/depts/biol/faculty/pdf/kaiser_et_al2013.pdf | journal=Herpetological Review | year= 2013| volume= 44| issue=1| pages= 8\u201323}}</ref>\n\nIn addition to red-bellied black snake, the species has been called common black snake, redbelly,  and RBBS.<ref name=ausmuseum>{{cite web | url=https://australianmuseum.net.au/Red-bellied-Black-Snake |title= Red-bellied Black Snake| work= Australian Museum website |publisher= Australian Museum | first=Cecilie | last=Beatson  | date= 5 May 2017 | accessdate=19 May 2017}}</ref>  It was known as ''djirrabidi'' to the [[Eora]] and [[Darug people|Darug]] inhabitants of the [[Sydney]] basin.<ref>{{cite book|author=Troy, Jakelin|year=1993|title=The Sydney Language|publisher=Self-published| location=Canberra|isbn=0-646-11015-2|page=53 | url=https://www.williamdawes.org/docs/troy_sydney_language_publication.pdf}}</ref>\n\n==Description==\nThe red-bellied black snake has a glossy black top body with a light-grey snout and brown mouth, {{sfn|Sutherland|Tibballs|2001|p=139}} and a completely black tail. It lacks a well-defined neck; its head merges seamlessly into the body.<ref name=reptilepark/> Its flanks are bright red or orange, fading to pink or dull red on the belly. All these scales have black margins.<ref name=shaw/> Snakes from northern populations tend to have lighter, more cream or pink bellies. The red-bellied black snake is on average around {{convert|1.25|m|abbr=on}} long, the largest individual recorded at {{convert|2.55|m|abbr=on}}.{{sfn|Sutherland|Tibballs|2001|p=139}}<!-- cites previous 2 sentences --> Males are generally slightly larger than females.<ref name=ausmuseum/> A large {{convert|2|m|adj=on|abbr=on}} specimen caught in Newcastle has been estimated to weigh around {{convert|10|kg|lb|abbr=on}}.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2014-10-02/snake-wrangler-catches-massive-red-bellied-black-snake-newcastle/5786950 |title=Massive red-bellied black snake surprises Newcastle wrangler called in to remove it | work=ABC News | date = 3 October 2014 |accessdate=4 Dec 2018 |author=Australian Broadcasting Corporation}}</ref> The red-bellied black snake can have a strong smell, which some field experts have used to find the snakes in the wild.{{sfn|Greer|1997|p=163}}\n\nLike all elapid snakes, it is [[Snake skeleton#Proteroglyph|proteroglyphous]] (front-fanged). Juveniles are similar to the [[eastern small-eyed snake]] (''Cryptophis nigrescens''), with which it can be easily confused, although the latter species lacks the red flanks.<ref name=reptilepark>{{cite web|url=http://www.reptilepark.com.au/animals.asp?catID=16&ID=116 |title=Red-bellied Black Snake |accessdate=28 December 2007 |author=Australian Reptile Park | location= Somersby, New South Wales  |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080103092555/http://www.reptilepark.com.au/animals.asp?catID=16&ID=116 |archivedate=3 January 2008 }}</ref> Other similar species include the [[blue-bellied black snake]] (''Pseudechis guttatus'') and copperheads of the genus ''[[Austrelaps]]''.<ref name=ausmuseum/> An early misconception was that the red-bellied black snake was [[sexual dimorphism|sexually dimorphic]], and that the [[eastern brown snake]] (''Pseudonaja textilis'') was the female form.<ref name=\"Bennett 60\">{{cite book |last1=Bennett |first1=George |title=Gatherings of a naturalist in Australasia : being observations principally on the animal and vegetable productions of New South Wales, New Zealand, and some of the Austral Islands |date=1860 |publisher=J. Van Voorst | location=London |pages=274\u201376 |url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/50146282}}</ref> This was recognised as such by Australian zoologist [[Gerard Krefft]] in his 1869 work ''Snakes of Australia''.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Krefft |first1=Gerard |title=The Snakes of Australia : an illustrated and descriptive catalogue of all the known species |date=1869 |publisher=T. Richards, Government Printer |pages=46\u201347 |url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/3678100| location=Sydney, New South Wales}}</ref>\n\n===Scalation===\n{{see also|Snake_scale#Nomenclature of scales}}\nThe number and arrangement of scales on a snake's body are a key element of identification to species level.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Hutchinson |first1=Mark | first2= Ian |last2=Williams |title=Key to the Snakes of South Australia |url=https://www.samuseum.sa.gov.au/Upload/Files-Biological-Sciences/R-and-A-text/Key-to-the-Snakes-of-South-Australia.pdf |website=South Australian Museum |publisher=Government of South Australia| date=2018 |accessdate=8 February 2019}}</ref> The red-bellied black snake has 17 rows of [[dorsal scales]] at midbody, 180 to 215 ventral scales, 48 to 60 [[subcaudal scales]] (the anterior\u2014and sometimes all\u2014subcaudals are undivided), and a divided [[anal scale]].{{efn|1=A divided scale is one split down the midline into two scales.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Macdonald |first1=Stewart |title=snake scale count search |url=http://www.arod.com.au/arod/scale/ |website=Australian Reptile Online Database |accessdate=3 May 2019}}</ref>}} There are two anterior and two posterior temporal scales, and the rostral shield is roughly square-shaped.{{sfn|Sutherland|Tibballs|2001|p=140}}\n\n==Distribution and habitat==\n[[File:Red-bellied Black Snake, Awabakal.jpg|thumb|right|Closeup, showing paler snout and forked tongue]]\nThe red-bellied black snake is native to the east coast of Australia, where it is one of the most commonly encountered snakes.<ref name=ausmuseum/> It can be found in the urban forest, woodland, plains, and bushland areas of the [[Blue Mountains (New South Wales)|Blue Mountains]], [[Canberra]], [[Sydney]], [[Brisbane]], [[Melbourne]], [[Cairns]], and [[Adelaide]]. The [[Macquarie Marshes]] mark a western border to its distribution in New South Wales,<ref name=shine87/> and [[Gladstone, Queensland|Gladstone]] in central Queensland marks the northern limit to the main population. To the south, it occurs across eastern and central Victoria, and extends along the Murray River into South Australia.{{sfn|Mirtschin|Rasmussen|Weinstein|2017|p=116}} Disjunct populations occur in the southern [[Mount Lofty Ranges]] in South Australia and in North Queensland.<ref name=ausmuseum/>\n\nThe red-bellied black snake is most commonly seen close to dams, streams, [[billabong]]s, and other bodies of water,<ref name=ausmuseum/> although they can venture up to {{convert|100|m|abbr=on|round=50}} away,<ref name=shine87/>\nincluding into nearby backyards.<ref name=reptilepark/> In particular, the red-bellied black snake prefers areas of shallow water with tangles of water plants, logs, or debris.<ref name=gilb35>{{cite journal | url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/38789700 | last=Gilbert | first=P.A. | year=1935 | title=The black snake  | journal=Proceedings of the Royal Zoological Society of New South Wales | volume=55  | pages=35\u201337}}</ref>\n\n==Behaviour==\nRed-bellied black snakes can hide in many places in their habitat, including logs, old mammal burrows, and grass tussocks.<ref name=shine87>{{cite journal | last=Shine |first= Richard | title=Intraspecific variation in thermoregulation, movements and habitat use by Australian blacksnakes, ''Pseudechis porphyriacus'' (Elapidae) | journal=Journal of Herpetology | year=1987 | pages= 165\u201377 | url=http://www.kingsnake.com/aho/pdf/menu3/shine1987c.pdf | volume=21 | issue=3 | doi=10.2307/1564479|jstor= 1564479 }}</ref><!-- cites previous 1.5 sentences --> They can flee into water and hide there; one was reported as staying submerged for 23 minutes. When swimming, they may hold their full head or the nostrils above the water's surface.{{sfn|Greer|1997|p=139}} At times, they may float without moving on the water surface, thus looking like a stick.{{sfn|Sutherland|Tibballs|2001|p=140}} Within their habitat, red-bellied black snakes appear to have ranges or territories with which they are familiar and generally remain within. A 1987 field study in three New South Wales localities found that these areas vary widely, from {{convert|0.02|to|40|ha|acre|abbr=on|sigfig=1}} in size.<ref name=shine87/> Within their territory, they may have some preferred places to reside.<ref name=ausmuseum/>\n\nThe red-bellied black snake is generally not an aggressive species, typically withdrawing when approached.{{sfn|Mirtschin|Rasmussen|Weinstein|2017|p=117}} If provoked, it recoils into a striking stance as a threat, holding its head and front part of its body horizontally above the ground and widening and flattening its neck. It may bite as a last resort.<ref name=ausmuseum/> It is generally active by day,{{sfn|Greer|1997|p=139}} though nighttime activity has occasionally been recorded.<ref name=shine87/> When not hunting or basking, it may be found beneath timber, rocks, and rubbish or down holes and burrows.<ref name=ausmuseum/>\n\nSnakes are active when their body temperatures are between {{convert|28|and|31|C|F|abbr=on|sigfig=2}}.<ref name=shine87/> They also [[Thermoregulation|thermoregulate]] by basking in warm, sunny spots in the cool, early morning and rest in shade in the middle of hot days, and may reduce their activity in hot, dry weather in late summer and autumn.{{sfn|Greer|1997|p=140}} Rather than entering true hibernation, red-bellied black snakes become relatively inactive over winter, retreating to cover and at times emerging on warm, sunny days. Their dark colour allows them to absorb heat from sunshine more quickly.{{sfn|Mirtschin|Rasmussen|Weinstein|2017|p=43}}<!-- cites previous two sentences --> In July 1949, six large individuals were found hibernating under a concrete slab in marshland in [[Woy Woy, New South Wales]].<ref>{{cite journal | last=Ormsby | first=A.I. | year=1952 | volume =71 | pages=25\u201327 | title=Notes on snake hibernation in New South Wales | journal=Proceedings of the Royal Zoological Society of New South Wales | url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/38792168}}</ref> Groups of up to six hibernating red-bellied black snakes have been recorded from under concrete slabs around [[Mount Druitt]] and [[Rooty Hill, New South Wales|Rooty Hill]] in western Sydney.<ref>{{cite journal | last=Hoser |first= Raymond T. | year=1980| title= Further records of aggregations of various species of Australian Snake | journal= Herpetofauna | volume= 12 | issue=1| pages= 16\u201322}}</ref><!-- cites previous two sentences --> Males are more active in the Southern Hemisphere spring (early October to November) as they roam looking for mates; one reportedly travelled {{convert|1220|m|mi|abbr=on|sigfig=2}} in a day. In summer, both sexes are less active generally.<ref name=ausmuseum/>\n\n===Reproduction===\nIn spring, male red-bellied black snakes often engage in ritualised combat for 2 to 30 minutes, even attacking other males already mating with females. They wrestle vigorously, but rarely bite, and engage in head-pushing contests, where each snake tries to push his opponent's head downward with his chin.<ref>{{cite journal | title=Mating and Male Combat in Australian Blacksnakes, ''Pseudechis porphyriacus'' |last=Shine | first=Richard| first2=Gordon C. | last2=Grigg | first3= Terri G. | last3=Shine | first4=Peter | last4=Harlow |url=https://sydney.edu.au/science/biology/shine/publications/reprints_legal/28matingmalecombat.pdf |journal =Journal of Herpetology | pages=101\u201307 | volume=15 | issue=1 | doi=10.2307/1563652|jstor=1563652 |year=1981 }}</ref>\n\nThe male seeks out a female and rubs his chin on her body, and may twitch, hiss, and rarely bite as he becomes aroused. The female indicates readiness to mate by straightening out and allowing their bodies to align. Pregnancy takes place any time from early spring to late summer. Females become much less active and band together in small groups in late pregnancy. They share the same retreat and bask in the sun together.<ref name=ausmuseum/> The red-bellied black snake is [[Ovoviviparity|ovoviviparous]]; that is, it gives birth to live young in individual membranous sacs,<ref name=ausmuseum/> after 14 weeks' gestation,{{sfn|Mirtschin|Rasmussen|Weinstein|2017|p=117}} usually in February or March.{{sfn|Sutherland|Tibballs|2001|p=141}} The young, numbering between eight and 40, emerge from their sacs very shortly after birth, and have an average length around {{convert|12.2|cm|abbr=on}}.<ref>{{cite book | last = Cogger | first = Harold G. | authorlink = Harold Cogger | title = Reptiles and Amphibians of Australia | publisher = Reed|origyear= 1979| year = 1983 | edition= Rev.| isbn = 978-0-88359-048-5 | page = 449 }}</ref> Young snakes almost triple their length and increase their weight 18-fold in their first year of life,<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Shine |first1=Richard |title=Growth Rates and Sexual Maturation in Six Species of Australian Elapid Snakes |journal=Herpetologica |date=1978 |volume=34 |issue=1 |pages=73\u201379 | jstor=3891614}}</ref> and are sexually mature when they reach [[wikt:svl|SVL]] (snout{{endash}}vent length) of {{convert|78|cm|abbr=on}} for males or {{convert|88|cm|abbr=on}} for females. Females can breed at around 31 months of age, while males can slightly earlier.{{sfn|Mirtschin|Rasmussen|Weinstein|2017|p=117}} Red-bellied black snakes can live up to 25 years.<ref name=eipper12/>\n\n===Feeding===\n[[File:Pseudechis porphyriacus eating eggs.jpg|thumb|right|Red-bellied black snake eating the eggs of a [[Dendrelaphis punctulatus|green tree snake]] near [[Dungog]], New South Wales ]]\nThe diet of red-bellied black snakes primarily consists of [[frog]]s, but they also prey on [[reptile]]s and small [[mammal]]s. They also eat other snakes, including those of their own species. Fish are hunted in water.<ref name=gilb35/> Red-bellied black snakes may hunt on or under the water surface, and prey can be eaten underwater or brought to the surface. They have been recorded stirring up substrate, possibly to disturb prey.<ref name=ausmuseum/> As red-bellied black snakes grow and mature, they continue to eat the same size prey, but add larger animals, as well.{{sfn|Greer|1997|p=145}} Although they prefer live food, red-bellied black snakes have been reported eating frogs squashed by cars.{{sfn|Greer|1997|p=147}}\n\nThey are susceptible to [[cane toad]] (''Rhinella marina'') toxins.{{sfn|Greer|1997|p=147}} The introduction of [[cane toads in Australia]] dates to 1935, when they were introduced in an attempt at biological control of native beetles, which were damaging sugarcane fields (a non-native plant). The intervention failed, mostly because the toads are on the ground, while the beetles feed on leaves at the top of the plant. One research study concluded that in less than 75 years, the red-bellied black snake had evolved in toad-inhabited regions of Australia to have increased resistance to toad toxin and decreased preference for toads as prey.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Phillips | first=Ben L. | last2= Shine |first2=Richard |title=An invasive species induces rapid adaptive change in a native predator: cane toads and black snakes in Australia |journal=Proceedings of the Royal Society B: Biological Sciences |volume=273 |issue=1593 |pages=1545\u201350 |year=2006 |pmid=16777750 |pmc=1560325 |doi=10.1098/rspb.2006.3479}}</ref>\n\n==Venom==\nEarly settlers feared the red-bellied black snake, though it turned out to be much less dangerous than many other species.{{sfn|Sutherland|Tibballs|2001|p=141}} The [[mice|murine]] [[median lethal dose]] (LD<sub>50</sub>) is 2.52&nbsp;mg/kg when administered [[subcutaneous injection|subcutaneously]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Broad | first= A. J.|last2=Sutherland| first2= S. K. |last3=Coulter| first3= A. R. |title=The lethality in mice of dangerous Australian and other snake venom |journal=Toxicon |date=1979 |volume=17 |issue=6 |pages=661\u201364 |pmid=524395| doi= 10.1016/0041-0101(79)90245-9}}</ref> A red-bellied black snake yields an average of 37&nbsp;mg of venom when milked, with the maximum recorded being 94&nbsp;mg.{{sfn|Sutherland|Tibballs|2001|p=141}} It accounted for 16% of identified snakebite victims in Australia between 2005 and 2015, with no deaths recorded.<ref>{{cite journal | first=Christopher I. |last= Johnston| first2=Nicole M |last2=Ryan | first3=Colin B |last3=Page| first4=Nicholas A |last4=Buckley | first5=Simon GA |last5=Brown | first6=Margaret A |last6=O'Leary| first7=Geoffrey K |last7=Isbister| title=The Australian Snakebite Project, 2005\u20132015 (ASP-20) |journal =Medical Journal of Australia |year=2017 | volume= 207 |issue=3|pages= 119\u201325 | doi= 10.5694/mja17.00094 |pmid= 28764620| url=http://www.emergpa.net/wp/wp-content/uploads/ASP-20.pdf}}</ref> Its venom contains [[neurotoxin]]s, [[myotoxin]]s, and [[Coagulation#Procoagulants|coagulants]] and also has [[Hemolysis|haemolytic]] properties.{{sfn|Mirtschin|Rasmussen|Weinstein|2017|p=119}}\n\n[[File:Red-bellied Black Snake (Pseudechis porphyriacus) (8397134493).jpg|thumb|right|Rearing in an aggressive posture, flattening of neck]]\nBites from red-bellied black snakes can be very painful\u2014needing [[analgesic|analgesia]]\u2014and result in local swelling, prolonged bleeding, and even local [[necrosis]],{{sfn|Mirtschin|Rasmussen|Weinstein|2017|p=101}} particularly if the bite is on a finger.{{sfn|Mirtschin|Rasmussen|Weinstein|2017|p=110}} Severe local reactions may require surgical debridement or even amputation.<ref name=weinstein18>{{cite journal |last1=Weinstein |first1=Scott |first2= Peter J.  |last2=Mirtschin |first3=Hamish |last3=Tristram |first4=Luke  |last4=Lawton |first5=Julian  |last5=White |title=Local morbidity from red-bellied black snake (''Pseudechis porphyriacus'', Elapidae) envenoming: Two cases and a brief review of management |journal=Toxicon |date=2018 |volume=142 |pages=34\u201341 |doi=10.1016/j.toxicon.2017.12.047|pmid=29269114 }}</ref> Symptoms of systemic envenomation\u2014including nausea, vomiting, headache, abdominal pain, [[diarrhoea]], or excessive sweating\u2014were thought to be rare, but a 2010 review found they occurred in most bite victims. Most people also go on to develop an anticoagulant [[coagulopathy]] in a few hours. This is characterised by a raised activated [[partial thromboplastin time]] (aPTT), and subsides over 24 hours. It resolves quickly with antivenom. A few people go on to develop a myotoxicity and associated generalised muscle pain and occasionally weakness, which may last up to 7 days. Patients may suffer a loss of sense of smell ([[anosmia]]);<ref name=mja>{{cite journal|url=https://www.mja.com.au/journal/2010/193/11/clinical-effects-red-bellied-black-snake-pseudechis-porphyriacus-envenoming-and|title=Clinical effects of red-bellied black snake (''Pseudechis porphyriacus'') envenoming and correlation with venom concentrations: Australian Snakebite Project (ASP-11) | first=Andrew |last=Churchman| first2= Margaret A |last2=O\u2019Leary| first3= Nicholas A |last3=Buckley| first4= Colin B |last4=Page| first5= Alan |last5=Tankel| first6= Chris |last6=Gavaghan| first7= Anna |last7=Holdgate| first8= Simon G A |last8=Brown| first9= Geoffrey K |last9=Isbister | journal=Medical Journal of Australia | year=2010 | volume= 193 |issue=11| pages= 696\u2013700|doi=10.5694/j.1326-5377.2010.tb04108.x }}</ref><!-- cites previous 4 sentences --> this is unrelated to the severity of the envenoming and can be temporary or permanent.{{sfn|Mirtschin|Rasmussen|Weinstein|2017|p=110}} Although the venom contains the [[three-finger toxin]] \u03b1-elapitoxin-Ppr1, which acts as a neurotoxin in laboratory experiments, neurotoxic symptoms are generally absent in clinical cases.{{sfn|Mirtschin|Rasmussen|Weinstein|2017|p=119}}\n\nA biologically active agent\u2014pseudexin\u2014was isolated from red-bellied black snake venom in 1981. Making up 25% of the venom, it is a single poly[[peptide]] chain with a molecular weight around 16.5 [[Atomic mass unit#Usage|kilodaltons]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Vaughan |first1=Gary T. | first2=Thomas B. | last2=Sculley | first3=Roy | last3=Tirrell |title=Isolation of a hemolytic, toxic phospholipase from the venom of the Australian red-bellied black snake (''Pseudechis porphyriacus'') |journal=Toxicon |date=1981 |volume=19 |issue=1 |pages=95\u2013101 |doi=10.1016/0041-0101(81)90121-5|pmid=7222091 }}</ref><!-- cites previous 2 sentences --> In 1989, it was found to be composed of three [[phospholipase A2]] isoenzymes.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Schmidt |first1=J.J. |last2=Middlebrook | first2=J.L. |title=Purification, sequencing and characterization of pseudexin phospholipases A2 from ''Pseudechis porphyriacus'' (Australian red-bellied black snake) |journal=Toxicon |date=1989 |volume=27 |issue=7 |pages=805\u201318 |pmid=2675391|doi=10.1016/0041-0101(89)90048-2 }}</ref> If antivenom is indicated, red-bellied black snake bites are generally treated with [[tiger snake]] antivenom.{{sfn|Sutherland|Tibballs|2001|p=142}} While black snake antivenom can be used, tiger snake antivenom can be used at a lower volume and is a cheaper treatment.<ref name=mja/>\n\nIt is the most commonly reported species responsible for envenomed dogs in New South Wales.<ref>{{cite journal | journal=Australian Veterinary Journal | year=2005 | volume=83| issue=5|pages=286\u201392 | title= Snake envenomation in dogs in New South Wales | last= Heller |first=J.| last2=Bosward |first2=K.L.| last3=Hodgson|first3=J.L.| last4=Cole|first4=F.L.| last5=Reid|first5=S.W.| last6=Hodgson|first6=D.R.| last7=Mellor|first7=D.J. | doi=10.1111/j.1751-0813.2005.tb12743.x| pmid=15957391 }}</ref> In 2006, a 12-year-old golden retriever suffered [[rhabdomyolysis]] and [[acute kidney injury]] secondary to a red-bellied black snake bite.<ref>{{cite journal | last=Heller|first= J.| last2= Bosward |first2=K. L.| last3=Hodgson |first3= D. R. | last4=Pottie |first4=R. |year=2006|title= Anuric renal failure in a dog after Red\u2010bellied Black snake (''Pseudechis porphyriacus'') envenomation | journal= Australian Veterinary Journal | volume= 84|issue=5| pages= 158\u201362|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/7042445 | doi=10.1111/j.1751-0813.2006.tb12769.x|pmid= 16739524}}</ref> Laboratory testing has found that cats are relatively resistant to the venom, with a lethal dose as high as 7&nbsp;mg/kg.{{sfn|Sutherland|Tibballs|2001|p=141}}\n\n==Conservation and threats==\nThe red-bellied black snake is considered to be a [[least-concern species]] according to the International Union for Conservation of Nature.<ref name=IUCN/> Its preferred habitat has been particularly vulnerable to urban development and is highly fragmented,<ref name=ausmuseum/> and a widespread decline in frogs, which are its preferred prey, has occurred. Snake numbers appear to have declined.{{sfn|Mirtschin|Rasmussen|Weinstein|2017|p=119}} [[Feral cat]]s are known to prey on red-bellied black snakes, while young snakes presumably are taken by [[laughing kookaburra]]s (''Dacelo novaeguineae''), [[brown falcon]]s (''Falco berigora''), and other [[Bird of prey|raptors]].<ref name=ausmuseum/>\n\n==Captivity==\nOne of the snakes commonly kept as pets in Australia,<ref name=eipper12>{{cite book | title=A Guide To \u2013 Australian Snakes in Captivity: Elapids & Colubrids |first= Scott |last=Eipper | publisher=Reptile Publications | year= 2012 | page=237  | isbn=978-0-9872447-8-9}}</ref> the red-bellied black snake adapts readily to captivity and lives on a supply of mice,<ref name=hoser2003/> though it can also survive on fish fillets, chicken, and dog food.<ref name=ausmuseum/>\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n== References ==\n=== Citations ===\n{{Reflist}}\n\n=== Cited books ===\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite book | last=Greer | first = Allen Ehh. | year=1997 | title = The Biology and Evolution of Australian Snakes | publisher= Surrey Beatty & Sons | location = Chipping Norton, New South Wales | isbn = 978-0-949324-68-9 | ref = harv }}\n* {{cite book  | last1 = Liddell  | first1 = Henry George  | author1-link = Henry Liddell  | last2 = Scott  | first2 = Robert  | author2-link = Robert Scott (philologist)  | year = 1980  | origyear = 1871  | edition = abridged  | title = A Greek-English Lexicon  | publisher = [[Oxford University Press]]  | location = Oxford, United Kingdom  | ref = harv | title-link = A Greek-English Lexicon }}\n* {{cite book | title = Australia's Dangerous Snakes: Identification, Biology and Envenoming  | first1 = Peter | last1 = Mirtschin | first2=  Arne | last2=Rasmussen | first3 = Scott | last3=Weinstein | publisher= Csiro Publishing |location=Clayton South, Victoria | year= 2017 | ref=harv |isbn=978-0-643-10674-1 }}\n* {{cite book |last1=Sutherland |first1=Struan K. |last2=Tibballs |first2=James |title=Australian Animal Toxins|edition=2nd |year=2001 |origyear=1983 |publisher=Oxford University Press |location=South Melbourne, Victoria  | ref = harv |isbn=978-0-19-550643-3 }}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060721061925/http://www.amonline.net.au/factsheets/snake_fangs.htm Pictures of Red-bellied Black Snake's fangs]\n\n{{Wikispecies-inline|Pseudechis porphyriacus}}\n{{Commons-inline|Pseudechis porphyriacus|''Pseudechis porphyriacus''}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q2005433}}\n\n[[Category:Elapidae]]\n[[Category:Endemic fauna of Australia]]\n[[Category:Snakes of Australia]]\n[[Category:Reptiles of New South Wales]]\n[[Category:Reptiles of Queensland]]\n[[Category:Reptiles of South Australia]]\n[[Category:Reptiles of Victoria (Australia)]]\n[[Category:Reptiles described in 1794]]\n[[Category:Taxa named by George Shaw]]\n", "text_old": "{{featured article}}\n{{short description|Highly venomous snake native to eastern Australia}}\n{{About|the snake native to Australia|the snake native to North America|Storeria occipitomaculata}}\n{{speciesbox\n| name = Red-bellied black snake\n | status              = LC\n | status_system       =  IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref name=IUCN>{{cite iucn | title = ''Pseudechis porphyriacus'' | volume= 2017 | page = e.T42493274A42493282 | year = 2017 | doi = 10.2305/IUCN.UK.2018-1.RLTS.T42493274A42493282.en }}</ref>\n| image = Pseudechis porphyriacus (35307320466).jpg\n| image_caption = At [[Lamington National Park]], Queensland\n| genus = Pseudechis\n| species = porphyriacus\n| authority = ([[George Shaw|Shaw]], 1794)\n| range_map = Red-Bellied Range.jpg\n| range_map_caption = Range of red-bellied black snake (in red)\n| synonyms_ref= <ref name=\"AFD\">{{cite web|url=https://biodiversity.org.au/afd/taxa/Pseudechis_porphyriacus |title=Species ''Pseudechis porphyriacus'' (Shaw, 1794) |author=Australian Biological Resources Study|date=26 August 2013|work=Australian Faunal Directory|publisher=Department of the Environment, Water, Heritage and the Arts, Australian Government|accessdate=6 December 2018|location=Canberra, Australian Capital Territory}}</ref><ref>{{EMBL species|genus=Pseudechis|species=porphyriacus}}. www.reptile-database.org.</ref>\n|synonyms= *''Coluber porphyriacus'' <br>{{small|Shaw, 1794}}\n* ''Trimeresurus leptocephalus'' <br>{{small|[[Bernard Germain de Lac\u00e9p\u00e8de|Lac\u00e9p\u00e8de]], 1804}}\n* ''Acanthophis tortor'' <br>{{small|[[Ren\u00e9 Lesson|Lesson]], 1830}}\n* ''Naja porphyrica'' <br>{{small|[[Hermann Schlegel|Schlegel]], 1837}}\n* ''Trimeresurus porphyreus'' <br>{{small|[[Andr\u00e9 Marie Constant Dum\u00e9ril|A.M.C. Dum\u00e9ril]] & [[Gabriel Bibron|Bibron]], 1854}}\n* ''Pseudechis porphyraicus'' [sic] <br>{{small|[[Frederick McCoy|F. McCoy]], 1867}}\n* ''Pseudechys'' [sic] ''porphyriacus'' <br>{{small|\u2014 F. McCoy, 1878}}\n* ''Pseudechis porphyriacus'' <br>{{small|\u2014 [[Harold Cogger|Cogger]], 1983}}\n}}\n\nThe '''red-bellied black snake''' (''Pseudechis porphyriacus'') is a [[species]] of [[venomous snake]] in the [[Family (biology)|family]] [[Elapidae]]. The species is [[endemic]] to [[Australia]]. Originally described by [[George Shaw]] in 1794 as a species new to science, it is one of eastern Australia's most commonly encountered snakes. Averaging around {{convert|1.25|m|abbr=on}} in length, it has glossy black upperparts, bright red or orange flanks, and a pink or dull red belly. It is not an aggressive species and generally retreats from encounters with people, but can attack if provoked.  Although its venom is capable of causing significant illness, no deaths have been recorded from its bite, which is less venomous than other Australian elapid snakes. The venom contains [[neurotoxin]]s, [[myotoxin]]s, and [[Coagulation#Procoagulants|coagulants]] and has [[Hemolysis|haemolytic]] properties; victims can also lose their sense of smell.\n\nCommon in woodlands, forests and swamplands, the red-bellied black snake often ventures into nearby urban areas. It forages in bodies of shallow water, commonly with tangles of water plants and logs, where it hunts its main prey item, frogs, as well as fish, reptiles, and small mammals. The snake is considered to be a [[least-concern species]] according to the [[International Union for Conservation of Nature]], but its numbers are thought to be declining due to habitat fragmentation and decline of frog populations.\n\n==Taxonomy==\nThe red-bellied black snake was first described and named by English naturalist [[George Shaw]] in ''Zoology of New Holland'' (1794) as ''Coluber porphyriacus''.<ref name=shaw/>  Incorrectly assuming it was harmless,<ref name=\"williams\"/> he wrote, \"This beautiful snake, which appears to be unprovided with tubular teeth or fangs, and consequently not of a venomous nature, is three, sometimes four, feet in nature.\"<ref name=shaw>{{cite book | last=Shaw | first=George | year=1794 |title=Zoology of New Holland | location= London, United Kingdom | publisher= J. Sowerby | pages=27\u201328|url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/40653632}}</ref> The species name is derived from the [[Ancient Greek]] ''porphyreus'', which can mean \"dark purple\", \"red-purple\" or \"beauteous\".{{sfn|Liddell|Scott|1980|p=579}} It was the first Australian [[Elapidae|elapid]] snake described.<ref name=\"williams\">{{cite journal|last=Williams|first=David|author2=W\u00fcster, Wolfgang |author2-link=Wolfgang W\u00fcster|author3=Fry, Bryan Grieg |year=2006|title= The good, the bad and the ugly: Australian snake taxonomists and a history of the taxonomy of Australia's venomous snakes|journal=Toxicon|volume=48|pages=919\u201330 |url=https://www.academia.edu/1163367|pmid=16999982|doi=10.1016/j.toxicon.2006.07.016|issue=7}}</ref> The [[syntype]] is presumed lost.<ref name=\"AFD\"/> French naturalist [[Bernard Germain de Lac\u00e9p\u00e8de]] described it under the name ''Trimeresurus leptocephalus'' in 1804.<ref>{{cite journal | last= Lac\u00e9p\u00e8de |first= B.G.E. | year= 1804| title= M\u00e9moire sur plusieurs animaux de la Nouvelle-Hollande dont la description n'a pas encore \u00e9t\u00e9 publi\u00e9e | journal= Annales du Mus\u00e9um National d'Histoire Naturelle. Paris | volume=4 |pages= 184\u2013211 [209]; [pl. 56 fig. 1] | url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/29642955}}</ref> His countryman [[Ren\u00e9 Lesson]] described it as ''Acanthophis tortor'' in 1826.<ref>{{cite book | author= Lesson, R.P. | year= 1826 | chapter= Reptiles. |editor= Duperrey, L.I. |title= Voyage Autour du Monde, Ex\u00e9cut\u00e9 par Ordre du Roi, sur la Corvette de sa Majest\u00e9, La Coquille, Pendant les Ann\u00e9es 1822, 1824 et 1825. Zoologie, Atlas |location= Paris |publisher= Arthus Bertrand | chapter-url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/38768324}}</ref> German biologist [[Hermann Schlegel]] felt it was allied with cobras and called it ''Naja porphyrica'' in 1837.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Schlegel |first1=Hermann |title=Essai sur la Physionomie des Serpens. Partie G\u00e9n\u00e9rale et Partie Descriptive |language=French | volume=2 |date=1837 |publisher=La Haye : Kips & Stockum |pages=479\u201380 |url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/3428921}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Pseudechis porphyriacus (Sowerby).jpg|thumb|left|\"''Coluber porphyriacus''\", ''Zoology and botany of New Holland'' (1794),<ref>Tab. X of: ''Zoology and botany of New Holland and the isles adjacent'' / the zoological part by [[George Shaw]], the botanical part by [[James Edward Smith]]; the figures by [[James Sowerby]].</ref><br>illustration from original description]]\nThe genus ''[[Pseudechis]]'' was created for it by German biologist [[Johann Georg Wagler]] in 1830,<ref>{{cite book | last=Wagler |first=Johann Georg | year= 1830 | title= Nat\u00fcrliches System der Amphibien, mit vorangehender Classification der S\u00e4ugethiere und Vogel | language=German| location=  Munich, Germany | publisher= Cotta'schen |page=[https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_YAsAAAAAQAAJ/page/n178 171] | url=https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_YAsAAAAAQAAJ}}</ref> to which several more species have been added subsequently.<ref>{{cite journal | last=Mackay| first= Roy D. | title= A revision of the genus ''Pseudechis'' | journal=  Proceedings of the Royal Zoological Society of New South Wales | volume= 74th | year=1953\u201354 | pages= 15\u201323 | url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/38812147}}</ref> The name is derived from the Ancient Greek words ''pseud\u0113s'' \"false\",{{sfn|Liddell|Scott|1980|p=795}} and ''echis'' \"viper\".{{sfn|Liddell|Scott|1980|p=295}} Snake expert [[Eric Worrell]], in 1961, analysed the skulls of the genus and found that of the red-bellied black snake to be the most divergent.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Worrell |first1=Eric |authorlink1=Eric Worrell |year=1961 |title=Herpetological name changes |journal=West Australian Naturalist |volume=8 |pages=18\u201327 |url=http://www.hotkeepers.com/aho/pdf/menu2/worrell1963.pdf |accessdate=2012-01-17 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120319192814/http://www.hotkeepers.com/aho/pdf/menu2/worrell1963.pdf |archivedate=2012-03-19 }}</ref> Its position as an early offshoot from the rest of the genus has been confirmed genetically in 2017.<ref name=\"Maddock\">{{Cite journal|last=Maddock|first=Simon T.|last2=Childerstone|first2=Aaron|last3=Fry|first3=Bryan Grieg|last4=Williams|first4=David J.|last5=Barlow|first5=Axel|last6=W\u00fcster|first6=Wolfgang|date=2017 |title=Multi-locus phylogeny and species delimitation of Australo-Papuan blacksnakes (''Pseudechis'' Wagler, 1830: Elapidae: Serpentes)|journal=Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution|volume=107|pages=48\u201355|doi=10.1016/j.ympev.2016.09.005|pmid=27637992|hdl=2436/621498|url=http://espace.library.uq.edu.au/view/UQ:412012/UQ412012_OA.pdf}}</ref>\n\nSnake handler [[Raymond Hoser]] described two extra subspecies in 2003: ''P. p. eipperi'' from the [[Atherton Tableland]] and surrounds in north-east Queensland, which he noted was smaller, rarely attaining 2&nbsp;m (7&nbsp;ft) and had a white or pale pink rather than red belly, and ''P. p.  rentoni'' from southeastern South Australia, which has a variably coloured (often orange or even blueish-tinged) belly. He added that both were disjunct from the main red-bellied black snake population, and as the distinguishing traits of ''P. p. rentoni'' were not consistent, then location was the most reliable way of identifying it.<ref name=hoser2003>{{cite journal | last=Hoser |first= Raymond| year= 2003| title= A re-assessment of the taxonomy of the Red-bellied Black Snakes (Genus ''Pseudechis'') with the descriptions of two new subspecies| journal = Boydii \u2013 Journal of the Herpetological Society of Queensland | issue=Autumn (May)|pages= 15\u201318 | url=http://www.smuggled.com/pdf1/PsePor1.pdf}}</ref> These subspecies have not been recognized by other authors,<ref name=\"AFD\"/> and Hoser has been strongly criticized for identifying some taxa on location alone, and omitting, misinterpreting or inventing evidence of distinctness.<ref name=kaiser13>{{cite journal |last=Kaiser | first= Hinrich | first2= Brian I. |last2=Crother | first3=C.M.R. |last3=Kelly | first4=Luca |last4=Luiselli | first5=Mark |last5=O'Shea | first6=Hidetoshi |last6=Ota | first7=Paulo |last7=Passos | first8=Wulf D. |last8=Schleip | first9=Wolfgang |last9=W\u00fcster | title=Best Practices: In the 21st Century, Taxonomic Decisions in Herpetology are Acceptable Only When Supported by a Body of Evidence and Published via Peer-Review | url=https://www.southeastern.edu/acad_research/depts/biol/faculty/pdf/kaiser_et_al2013.pdf | journal=Herpetological Review | year= 2013| volume= 44| issue=1| pages= 8\u201323}}</ref>\n\nIn addition to red-bellied black snake, the species has been called common black snake, redbelly,  and RBBS.<ref name=ausmuseum>{{cite web | url=https://australianmuseum.net.au/Red-bellied-Black-Snake |title= Red-bellied Black Snake| work= Australian Museum website |publisher= Australian Museum | first=Cecilie | last=Beatson  | date= 5 May 2017 | accessdate=19 May 2017}}</ref>  It was known as ''djirrabidi'' to the [[Eora]] and [[Darug people|Darug]] inhabitants of the [[Sydney]] basin.<ref>{{cite book|author=Troy, Jakelin|year=1993|title=The Sydney Language|publisher=Self-published| location=Canberra|isbn=0-646-11015-2|page=53 | url=https://www.williamdawes.org/docs/troy_sydney_language_publication.pdf}}</ref>\n\n==Description==\nThe red-bellied black snake has a glossy black top body with a light-grey snout and brown mouth, {{sfn|Sutherland|Tibballs|2001|p=139}} and a completely black tail. It lacks a well-defined neck; its head merges seamlessly into the body.<ref name=reptilepark/> Its flanks are bright red or orange, fading to pink or dull red on the belly. All these scales have black margins.<ref name=shaw/> Snakes from northern populations tend to have lighter, more cream or pink bellies. The red-bellied black snake is on average around {{convert|1.25|m|abbr=on}} long, the largest individual recorded at {{convert|2.55|m|abbr=on}}.{{sfn|Sutherland|Tibballs|2001|p=139}}<!-- cites previous 2 sentences --> Males are generally slightly larger than females.<ref name=ausmuseum/> A large {{convert|2|m|adj=on|abbr=on}} specimen caught in Newcastle has been estimated to weigh around {{convert|10|kg|lb|abbr=on}}.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2014-10-02/snake-wrangler-catches-massive-red-bellied-black-snake-newcastle/5786950 |title=Massive red-bellied black snake surprises Newcastle wrangler called in to remove it | work=ABC News | date = 3 October 2014 |accessdate=4 Dec 2018 |author=Australian Broadcasting Corporation}}</ref> The red-bellied black snake can have a strong smell, which some field experts have used to find the snakes in the wild.{{sfn|Greer|1997|p=163}}\n\nLike all elapid snakes, it is [[Snake skeleton#Proteroglyph|proteroglyphous]] (front-fanged). Juveniles are similar to the [[eastern small-eyed snake]] (''Cryptophis nigrescens''), with which it can be easily confused, although the latter species lacks the red flanks.<ref name=reptilepark>{{cite web|url=http://www.reptilepark.com.au/animals.asp?catID=16&ID=116 |title=Red-bellied Black Snake |accessdate=28 December 2007 |author=Australian Reptile Park | location= Somersby, New South Wales  |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080103092555/http://www.reptilepark.com.au/animals.asp?catID=16&ID=116 |archivedate=3 January 2008 }}</ref> Other similar species include the [[blue-bellied black snake]] (''Pseudechis guttatus'') and copperheads of the genus ''[[Austrelaps]]''.<ref name=ausmuseum/> An early misconception was that the red-bellied black snake was [[sexual dimorphism|sexually dimorphic]], and that the [[eastern brown snake]] (''Pseudonaja textilis'') was the female form.<ref name=\"Bennett 60\">{{cite book |last1=Bennett |first1=George |title=Gatherings of a naturalist in Australasia : being observations principally on the animal and vegetable productions of New South Wales, New Zealand, and some of the Austral Islands |date=1860 |publisher=J. Van Voorst | location=London |pages=274\u201376 |url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/50146282}}</ref> This was recognised as such by Australian zoologist [[Gerard Krefft]] in his 1869 work ''Snakes of Australia''.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Krefft |first1=Gerard |title=The Snakes of Australia : an illustrated and descriptive catalogue of all the known species |date=1869 |publisher=T. Richards, Government Printer |pages=46\u201347 |url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/3678100| location=Sydney, New South Wales}}</ref>\n\n===Scalation===\n{{see also|Snake_scale#Nomenclature of scales}}\nThe number and arrangement of scales on a snake's body are a key element of identification to species level.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Hutchinson |first1=Mark | first2= Ian |last2=Williams |title=Key to the Snakes of South Australia |url=https://www.samuseum.sa.gov.au/Upload/Files-Biological-Sciences/R-and-A-text/Key-to-the-Snakes-of-South-Australia.pdf |website=South Australian Museum |publisher=Government of South Australia| date=2018 |accessdate=8 February 2019}}</ref> The red-bellied black snake has 17 rows of [[dorsal scales]] at midbody, 180 to 215 ventral scales, 48 to 60 [[subcaudal scales]] (the anterior\u2014and sometimes all\u2014subcaudals are undivided), and a divided [[anal scale]].{{efn|1=A divided scale is one split down the midline into two scales.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Macdonald |first1=Stewart |title=snake scale count search |url=http://www.arod.com.au/arod/scale/ |website=Australian Reptile Online Database |accessdate=3 May 2019}}</ref>}} There are two anterior and two posterior temporal scales, and the rostral shield is roughly square-shaped.{{sfn|Sutherland|Tibballs|2001|p=140}}\n\n==Distribution and habitat==\n[[File:Red-bellied Black Snake, Awabakal.jpg|thumb|right|Closeup, showing paler snout and forked tongue]]\nThe red-bellied black snake is native to the east coast of Australia, where it is one of the most commonly encountered snakes.<ref name=ausmuseum/> It can be found in the urban forest, woodland, plains, and bushland areas of the [[Blue Mountains (New South Wales)|Blue Mountains]], [[Canberra]], [[Sydney]], [[Brisbane]], [[Melbourne]], [[Cairns]], and [[Adelaide]]. The [[Macquarie Marshes]] mark a western border to its distribution in New South Wales,<ref name=shine87/> and [[Gladstone, Queensland|Gladstone]] in central Queensland marks the northern limit to the main population. To the south, it occurs across eastern and central Victoria, and extends along the Murray River into South Australia.{{sfn|Mirtschin|Rasmussen|Weinstein|2017|p=116}} Disjunct populations occur in the southern [[Mount Lofty Ranges]] in South Australia and in North Queensland.<ref name=ausmuseum/>\n\nThe red-bellied black snake is most commonly seen close to dams, streams, [[billabong]]s, and other bodies of water,<ref name=ausmuseum/> although they can venture up to {{convert|100|m|abbr=on|round=50}} away,<ref name=shine87/>\nincluding into nearby backyards.<ref name=reptilepark/> In particular, the red-bellied black snake prefers areas of shallow water with tangles of water plants, logs, or debris.<ref name=gilb35>{{cite journal | url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/38789700 | last=Gilbert | first=P.A. | year=1935 | title=The black snake  | journal=Proceedings of the Royal Zoological Society of New South Wales | volume=55  | pages=35\u201337}}</ref>\n\n==Behaviour==\nRed-bellied black snakes can hide in many places in their habitat, including logs, old mammal burrows, and grass tussocks.<ref name=shine87>{{cite journal | last=Shine |first= Richard | title=Intraspecific variation in thermoregulation, movements and habitat use by Australian blacksnakes, ''Pseudechis porphyriacus'' (Elapidae) | journal=Journal of Herpetology | year=1987 | pages= 165\u201377 | url=http://www.kingsnake.com/aho/pdf/menu3/shine1987c.pdf | volume=21 | issue=3 | doi=10.2307/1564479|jstor= 1564479 }}</ref><!-- cites previous 1.5 sentences --> They can flee into water and hide there; one was reported as staying submerged for 23 minutes. When swimming, they may hold their full head or the nostrils above the water's surface.{{sfn|Greer|1997|p=139}} At times, they may float without moving on the water surface, thus looking like a stick.{{sfn|Sutherland|Tibballs|2001|p=140}} Within their habitat, red-bellied black snakes appear to have ranges or territories with which they are familiar and generally remain within. A 1987 field study in three New South Wales localities found that these areas vary widely, from {{convert|0.02|to|40|ha|acre|abbr=on|sigfig=1}} in size.<ref name=shine87/> Within their territory, they may have some preferred places to reside.<ref name=ausmuseum/>\n\nThe red-bellied black snake is generally not an aggressive species, typically withdrawing when approached.{{sfn|Mirtschin|Rasmussen|Weinstein|2017|p=117}} If provoked, it recoils into a striking stance as a threat, holding its head and front part of its body horizontally above the ground and widening and flattening its neck. It may bite as a last resort.<ref name=ausmuseum/> It is generally active by day,{{sfn|Greer|1997|p=139}} though nighttime activity has occasionally been recorded.<ref name=shine87/> When not hunting or basking, it may be found beneath timber, rocks, and rubbish or down holes and burrows.<ref name=ausmuseum/>\n\nSnakes are active when their body temperatures are between {{convert|28|and|31|C|F|abbr=on|sigfig=2}}.<ref name=shine87/> They also [[Thermoregulation|thermoregulate]] by basking in warm, sunny spots in the cool, early morning and rest in shade in the middle of hot days, and may reduce their activity in hot, dry weather in late summer and autumn.{{sfn|Greer|1997|p=140}} Rather than entering true hibernation, red-bellied black snakes become relatively inactive over winter, retreating to cover and at times emerging on warm, sunny days. Their dark colour allows them to absorb heat from sunshine more quickly.{{sfn|Mirtschin|Rasmussen|Weinstein|2017|p=43}}<!-- cites previous two sentences --> In July 1949, six large individuals were found hibernating under a concrete slab in marshland in [[Woy Woy, New South Wales]].<ref>{{cite journal | last=Ormsby | first=A.I. | year=1952 | volume =71 | pages=25\u201327 | title=Notes on snake hibernation in New South Wales | journal=Proceedings of the Royal Zoological Society of New South Wales | url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/38792168}}</ref> Groups of up to six hibernating red-bellied black snakes have been recorded from under concrete slabs around [[Mount Druitt]] and [[Rooty Hill, New South Wales|Rooty Hill]] in western Sydney.<ref>{{cite journal | last=Hoser |first= Raymond T. | year=1980| title= Further records of aggregations of various species of Australian Snake | journal= Herpetofauna | volume= 12 | issue=1| pages= 16\u201322}}</ref><!-- cites previous two sentences --> Males are more active in the Southern Hemisphere spring (early October to November) as they roam looking for mates; one reportedly travelled {{convert|1220|m|mi|abbr=on|sigfig=2}} in a day. In summer, both sexes are less active generally.<ref name=ausmuseum/>\n\n===Reproduction===\nIn spring, male red-bellied black snakes often engage in ritualised combat for 2 to 30 minutes, even attacking other males already mating with females. They wrestle vigorously, but rarely bite, and engage in head-pushing contests, where each snake tries to push his opponent's head downward with his chin.<ref>{{cite journal | title=Mating and Male Combat in Australian Blacksnakes, ''Pseudechis porphyriacus'' |last=Shine | first=Richard| first2=Gordon C. | last2=Grigg | first3= Terri G. | last3=Shine | first4=Peter | last4=Harlow |url=https://sydney.edu.au/science/biology/shine/publications/reprints_legal/28matingmalecombat.pdf |journal =Journal of Herpetology | pages=101\u201307 | volume=15 | issue=1 | doi=10.2307/1563652|jstor=1563652 |year=1981 }}</ref>\n\nThe male seeks out a female and rubs his chin on her body, and may twitch, hiss, and rarely bite as he becomes aroused. The female indicates readiness to mate by straightening out and allowing their bodies to align. Pregnancy takes place any time from early spring to late summer. Females become much less active and band together in small groups in late pregnancy. They share the same retreat and bask in the sun together.<ref name=ausmuseum/> The red-bellied black snake is [[Ovoviviparity|ovoviviparous]]; that is, it gives birth to live young in individual membranous sacs,<ref name=ausmuseum/> after 14 weeks' gestation,{{sfn|Mirtschin|Rasmussen|Weinstein|2017|p=117}} usually in February or March.{{sfn|Sutherland|Tibballs|2001|p=141}} The young, numbering between eight and 40, emerge from their sacs very shortly after birth, and have an average length around {{convert|12.2|cm|abbr=on}}.<ref>{{cite book | last = Cogger | first = Harold G. | authorlink = Harold Cogger | title = Reptiles and Amphibians of Australia | publisher = Reed|origyear= 1979| year = 1983 | edition= Rev.| isbn = 978-0-88359-048-5 | page = 449 }}</ref> Young snakes almost triple their length and increase their weight 18-fold in their first year of life,<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Shine |first1=Richard |title=Growth Rates and Sexual Maturation in Six Species of Australian Elapid Snakes |journal=Herpetologica |date=1978 |volume=34 |issue=1 |pages=73\u201379 | jstor=3891614}}</ref> and are sexually mature when they reach [[wikt:svl|SVL]] (snout{{endash}}vent length) of {{convert|78|cm|abbr=on}} for males or {{convert|88|cm|abbr=on}} for females. Females can breed at around 31 months of age, while males can slightly earlier.{{sfn|Mirtschin|Rasmussen|Weinstein|2017|p=117}} Red-bellied black snakes can live up to 25 years.<ref name=eipper12/>\n\n===Feeding===\n[[File:Pseudechis porphyriacus eating eggs.jpg|thumb|right|Red-bellied black snake eating the eggs of a [[Dendrelaphis punctulatus|green tree snake]] near [[Dungog]], New South Wales ]]\nThe diet of red-bellied black snakes primarily consists of [[frog]]s, but they also prey on [[reptile]]s and small [[mammal]]s. They also eat other snakes, including those of their own species. Fish are hunted in water.<ref name=gilb35/> Red-bellied black snakes may hunt on or under the water surface, and prey can be eaten underwater or brought to the surface. They have been recorded stirring up substrate, possibly to disturb prey.<ref name=ausmuseum/> As red-bellied black snakes grow and mature, they continue to eat the same size prey, but add larger animals, as well.{{sfn|Greer|1997|p=145}} Although they prefer live food, red-bellied black snakes have been reported eating frogs squashed by cars.{{sfn|Greer|1997|p=147}}\n\nThey are susceptible to [[cane toad]] (''Rhinella marina'') toxins.{{sfn|Greer|1997|p=147}} The introduction of [[cane toads in Australia]] dates to 1935, when they were introduced in an attempt at biological control of native beetles, which were damaging sugarcane fields (a non-native plant). The intervention failed, mostly because the toads are on the ground, while the beetles feed on leaves at the top of the plant. One research study concluded that in less than 75 years, the red-bellied black snake had evolved in toad-inhabited regions of Australia to have increased resistance to toad toxin and decreased preference for toads as prey.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Phillips | first=Ben L. | last2= Shine |first2=Richard |title=An invasive species induces rapid adaptive change in a native predator: cane toads and black snakes in Australia |journal=Proceedings of the Royal Society B: Biological Sciences |volume=273 |issue=1593 |pages=1545\u201350 |year=2006 |pmid=16777750 |pmc=1560325 |doi=10.1098/rspb.2006.3479}}</ref>\n\n==Venom==\nEarly settlers feared the red-bellied black snake, though it turned out to be much less dangerous than many other species.{{sfn|Sutherland|Tibballs|2001|p=141}} The [[mice|murine]] [[median lethal dose]] (LD<sub>50</sub>) is 2.52&nbsp;mg/kg when administered [[subcutaneous injection|subcutaneously]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Broad | first= A. J.|last2=Sutherland| first2= S. K. |last3=Coulter| first3= A. R. |title=The lethality in mice of dangerous Australian and other snake venom |journal=Toxicon |date=1979 |volume=17 |issue=6 |pages=661\u201364 |pmid=524395| doi= 10.1016/0041-0101(79)90245-9}}</ref> A red-bellied black snake yields an average of 37&nbsp;mg of venom when milked, with the maximum recorded being 94&nbsp;mg.{{sfn|Sutherland|Tibballs|2001|p=141}} It accounted for 16% of identified snakebite victims in Australia between 2005 and 2015, with no deaths recorded.<ref>{{cite journal | first=Christopher I. |last= Johnston| first2=Nicole M |last2=Ryan | first3=Colin B |last3=Page| first4=Nicholas A |last4=Buckley | first5=Simon GA |last5=Brown | first6=Margaret A |last6=O'Leary| first7=Geoffrey K |last7=Isbister| title=The Australian Snakebite Project, 2005\u20132015 (ASP-20) |journal =Medical Journal of Australia |year=2017 | volume= 207 |issue=3|pages= 119\u201325 | doi= 10.5694/mja17.00094 |pmid= 28764620| url=http://www.emergpa.net/wp/wp-content/uploads/ASP-20.pdf}}</ref> Its venom contains [[neurotoxin]]s, [[myotoxin]]s, and [[Coagulation#Procoagulants|coagulants]] and also has [[Hemolysis|haemolytic]] properties.{{sfn|Mirtschin|Rasmussen|Weinstein|2017|p=119}}\n\n[[File:Red-bellied Black Snake (Pseudechis porphyriacus) (8397134493).jpg|thumb|right|Rearing in an aggressive posture, flattening of neck]]\nBites from red-bellied black snakes can be very painful\u2014needing [[analgesic|analgesia]]\u2014and result in local swelling, prolonged bleeding, and even local [[necrosis]],{{sfn|Mirtschin|Rasmussen|Weinstein|2017|p=101}} particularly if the bite is on a finger.{{sfn|Mirtschin|Rasmussen|Weinstein|2017|p=110}} Severe local reactions may require surgical debridement or even amputation.<ref name=weinstein18>{{cite journal |last1=Weinstein |first1=Scott |first2= Peter J.  |last2=Mirtschin |first3=Hamish |last3=Tristram |first4=Luke  |last4=Lawton |first5=Julian  |last5=White |title=Local morbidity from red-bellied black snake (''Pseudechis porphyriacus'', Elapidae) envenoming: Two cases and a brief review of management |journal=Toxicon |date=2018 |volume=142 |pages=34\u201341 |doi=10.1016/j.toxicon.2017.12.047|pmid=29269114 }}</ref> Symptoms of systemic envenomation\u2014including nausea, vomiting, headache, abdominal pain, [[diarrhoea]], or excessive sweating\u2014were thought to be rare, but a 2010 review found they occurred in most bite victims. Most people also go on to develop an anticoagulant [[coagulopathy]] in a few hours. This is characterised by a raised activated [[partial thromboplastin time]] (aPTT), and subsides over 24 hours. It resolves quickly with antivenom. A few people go on to develop a myotoxicity and associated generalised muscle pain and occasionally weakness, which may last up to 7 days. Patients may suffer a loss of sense of smell ([[anosmia]]);<ref name=mja>{{cite journal|url=https://www.mja.com.au/journal/2010/193/11/clinical-effects-red-bellied-black-snake-pseudechis-porphyriacus-envenoming-and|title=Clinical effects of red-bellied black snake (''Pseudechis porphyriacus'') envenoming and correlation with venom concentrations: Australian Snakebite Project (ASP-11) | first=Andrew |last=Churchman| first2= Margaret A |last2=O\u2019Leary| first3= Nicholas A |last3=Buckley| first4= Colin B |last4=Page| first5= Alan |last5=Tankel| first6= Chris |last6=Gavaghan| first7= Anna |last7=Holdgate| first8= Simon G A |last8=Brown| first9= Geoffrey K |last9=Isbister | journal=Medical Journal of Australia | year=2010 | volume= 193 |issue=11| pages= 696\u2013700|doi=10.5694/j.1326-5377.2010.tb04108.x }}</ref><!-- cites previous 4 sentences --> this is unrelated to the severity of the envenoming and can be temporary or permanent.{{sfn|Mirtschin|Rasmussen|Weinstein|2017|p=110}} Although the venom contains the [[three-finger toxin]] \u03b1-elapitoxin-Ppr1, which acts as a neurotoxin in laboratory experiments, neurotoxic symptoms are generally absent in clinical cases.{{sfn|Mirtschin|Rasmussen|Weinstein|2017|p=119}}\n\nA biologically active agent\u2014pseudexin\u2014was isolated from red-bellied black snake venom in 1981. Making up 25% of the venom, it is a single poly[[peptide]] chain with a molecular weight around 16.5 [[Atomic mass unit#Usage|kilodaltons]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Vaughan |first1=Gary T. | first2=Thomas B. | last2=Sculley | first3=Roy | last3=Tirrell |title=Isolation of a hemolytic, toxic phospholipase from the venom of the Australian red-bellied black snake (''Pseudechis porphyriacus'') |journal=Toxicon |date=1981 |volume=19 |issue=1 |pages=95\u2013101 |doi=10.1016/0041-0101(81)90121-5|pmid=7222091 }}</ref><!-- cites previous 2 sentences --> In 1989, it was found to be composed of three [[phospholipase A2]] isoenzymes.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Schmidt |first1=J.J. |last2=Middlebrook | first2=J.L. |title=Purification, sequencing and characterization of pseudexin phospholipases A2 from ''Pseudechis porphyriacus'' (Australian red-bellied black snake) |journal=Toxicon |date=1989 |volume=27 |issue=7 |pages=805\u201318 |pmid=2675391|doi=10.1016/0041-0101(89)90048-2 }}</ref> If antivenom is indicated, red-bellied black snake bites are generally treated with [[tiger snake]] antivenom.{{sfn|Sutherland|Tibballs|2001|p=142}} While black snake antivenom can be used, tiger snake antivenom can be used at a lower volume and is a cheaper treatment.<ref name=mja/>\n\nIt is the most commonly reported species responsible for envenomed dogs in New South Wales.<ref>{{cite journal | journal=Australian Veterinary Journal | year=2005 | volume=83| issue=5|pages=286\u201392 | title= Snake envenomation in dogs in New South Wales | last= Heller |first=J.| last2=Bosward |first2=K.L.| last3=Hodgson|first3=J.L.| last4=Cole|first4=F.L.| last5=Reid|first5=S.W.| last6=Hodgson|first6=D.R.| last7=Mellor|first7=D.J. | doi=10.1111/j.1751-0813.2005.tb12743.x| pmid=15957391 }}</ref> In 2006, a 12-year-old golden retriever suffered [[rhabdomyolysis]] and [[acute kidney injury]] secondary to a red-bellied black snake bite.<ref>{{cite journal | last=Heller|first= J.| last2= Bosward |first2=K. L.| last3=Hodgson |first3= D. R. | last4=Pottie |first4=R. |year=2006|title= Anuric renal failure in a dog after Red\u2010bellied Black snake (''Pseudechis porphyriacus'') envenomation | journal= Australian Veterinary Journal | volume= 84|issue=5| pages= 158\u201362|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/7042445 | doi=10.1111/j.1751-0813.2006.tb12769.x|pmid= 16739524}}</ref> Laboratory testing has found that cats are relatively resistant to the venom, with a lethal dose as high as 7&nbsp;mg/kg.{{sfn|Sutherland|Tibballs|2001|p=141}}\n\n==Conservation and threats==\nThe red-bellied black snake is considered to be a [[least-concern species]] according to the International Union for Conservation of Nature.<ref name=IUCN/> Its preferred habitat has been particularly vulnerable to urban development and is highly fragmented,<ref name=ausmuseum/> and a widespread decline in frogs, which are its preferred prey, has occurred. Snake numbers appear to have declined.{{sfn|Mirtschin|Rasmussen|Weinstein|2017|p=119}} [[Feral cat]]s are known to prey on red-bellied black snakes, while young snakes presumably are taken by [[laughing kookaburra]]s (''Dacelo novaeguineae''), [[brown falcon]]s (''Falco berigora''), and other [[Bird of prey|raptors]].<ref name=ausmuseum/>\n\n==Captivity==\nOne of the snakes commonly kept as pets in Australia,<ref name=eipper12>{{cite book | title=A Guide To \u2013 Australian Snakes in Captivity: Elapids & Colubrids |first= Scott |last=Eipper | publisher=Reptile Publications | year= 2012 | page=237  | isbn=978-0-9872447-8-9}}</ref> the red-bellied black snake adapts readily to captivity and lives on a supply of mice,<ref name=hoser2003/> though it can also survive on fish fillets, chicken, and dog food.<ref name=ausmuseum/>\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n== References ==\n=== Citations ===\n{{Reflist}}\n\n=== Cited books ===\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite book | last=Greer | first = Allen E. | year=1997 | title = The Biology and Evolution of Australian Snakes | publisher= Surrey Beatty & Sons | location = Chipping Norton, New South Wales | isbn = 978-0-949324-68-9 | ref = harv }}\n* {{cite book  | last1 = Liddell  | first1 = Henry George  | author1-link = Henry Liddell  | last2 = Scott  | first2 = Robert  | author2-link = Robert Scott (philologist)  | year = 1980  | origyear = 1871  | edition = abridged  | title = A Greek-English Lexicon  | publisher = [[Oxford University Press]]  | location = Oxford, United Kingdom  | ref = harv | title-link = A Greek-English Lexicon }}\n* {{cite book | title = Australia's Dangerous Snakes: Identification, Biology and Envenoming  | first1 = Peter | last1 = Mirtschin | first2=  Arne | last2=Rasmussen | first3 = Scott | last3=Weinstein | publisher= Csiro Publishing |location=Clayton South, Victoria | year= 2017 | ref=harv |isbn=978-0-643-10674-1 }}\n* {{cite book |last1=Sutherland |first1=Struan K. |last2=Tibballs |first2=James |title=Australian Animal Toxins|edition=2nd |year=2001 |origyear=1983 |publisher=Oxford University Press |location=South Melbourne, Victoria  | ref = harv |isbn=978-0-19-550643-3 }}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060721061925/http://www.amonline.net.au/factsheets/snake_fangs.htm Pictures of Red-bellied Black Snake's fangs]\n\n{{Wikispecies-inline|Pseudechis porphyriacus}}\n{{Commons-inline|Pseudechis porphyriacus|''Pseudechis porphyriacus''}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q2005433}}\n\n[[Category:Elapidae]]\n[[Category:Endemic fauna of Australia]]\n[[Category:Snakes of Australia]]\n[[Category:Reptiles of New South Wales]]\n[[Category:Reptiles of Queensland]]\n[[Category:Reptiles of South Australia]]\n[[Category:Reptiles of Victoria (Australia)]]\n[[Category:Reptiles described in 1794]]\n[[Category:Taxa named by George Shaw]]\n", "name_user": "2406:3400:51f:df60:3dc1:e3eb:ab84:c0be", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eCited books)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Red-bellied_black_snake"}
